No liberating amendment for Tymoshenko by Parliament
The Ukrainian parliament today denied a motion to repeal, as part of an amendment to the Criminal Code, the article on which opposition leader Yulia Timoshenko was convicted.
The new regulation, which could have paved the way for the liberation of the imprisoned prime minister, was rejected by MEPs at the second reading of the motion to reduce the penalties for economic offences.
Timoshenko was sentenced to seven years in prison in October for concluding a supposedly adverse gas purchase contract with Russia.
The verdict is not yet final, and the convicts' appeal will be heard in court in December.
Timoshenko himself calls the verdict a political revenge of the regime, and in the West, too, the trial has raised suspicions of court bias.
The motion to remove from the Criminal Code paragraph 365, on the basis of which the prime minister was convicted, was supported by 147 Members.
226 votes would have been required for its adoption.
