Beginning of a New Crisis Era
France and the rest of Europe in the focus of investors.
On Tuesday, a statistical storm swept through Europe.
National governments published their GDP data for the third quarter.
The Czech economy stagnated compared to the previous quarter, with Germany and France growing.
Today, however, the bond market is breaking all records.
Investors are watching not only Greece, but now Spain, France, Austria, and other countries as well.
The statistical offices of the European zone, Germany, the Czech Republic and some other European countries published their preliminary economic forecasts for the third quarter.
Germany ’ s GDP grew by 0.5% as expected, and that of France by 0.4%.
Both countries simultaneously revised their data for the second quarter, when growth in Germany was higher than originally expected (growth of 0.3% instead of the 0.1% forecast), while France admitted a slight decline of 0.1% (initial figures only spoke of stagnation).
This year ’ s third quarter saw the Czech economy grow by 1.5 percent compared to the previous year.
Compared to the previous quarter, however, gross domestic product stagnated and, according to the Czech Statistical Office, this confirmed the trend of a slowdown in economic performance.
The results are therefore worse than analysts' forecasts.
The main events:
The Czech economy grew by 1.5 percent in the third quarter of this year compared to the previous year, but stagnated compared to the previous quarter.
According to preliminary and seasonal data, the German economy grew by 0.5 percent in the third quarter.
In the euro area as a whole and in the EU, the economy grew by 0.2% between July and September compared to the previous quarter, in line with analysts ’ expectations.
The Greek economy contracted by 5.2 percent compared to the previous year.
The yield on their 10-year government bonds soared to 28.45%.
The yield on Italian and Spanish government bonds rose to its critical limits.
Also Austria, the Netherlands, France, Belgium and other countries are beginning to feel problems...
Yields on Czech government bonds remain below 4%, although the situation in the region is deteriorating.
In Germany, voices are being raised that the ECB should become the creditor of last resort.
