Iranian students are willing to die for their country ’ s core program.
They formed a living shield.
A few hundred college students formed a live sign around a nuclear object in Iran.
With this gesture they wanted to demonstrate their support for the core programme of their country before a possible Israeli attack.
The students prayed in front of the object at noon on Tuesday and then announced their death to the USA and Israel.
A few hundred students from the university in Isfahan, Iran, formed a live sign around the nuclear technology center in Isfahan, where uranium is processed, on Tuesday.
They wanted to show that they are prepared to protect the core programme of their country, if necessary with their own lives.
The International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) recently stated in its report that Iran appears to have not given up its efforts to acquire a nuclear weapon.
In Israel, too, there is talk of a possible attack on Iranian nuclear installations.
At noon, students prayed outside the entrance to the complex and then proclaimed death to the United States and Israel.
According to the Israeli press, in the event of an attack intended to paralyze Iran ’ s nuclear program, the nuclear enrichment facility at the center of Isfahan would also be targeted.
The menu of a fatty child: it does not have breakfast and eats sausage with dinner
More than one third of children aged 9 to 13 have problems with obesity, with 9 percent of all pupils and 5 percent of all children being overweight.
Recent surveys have shown - obese children mostly come from families with unhealthy lifestyles.
Once again, this shows how important the environment in which a person grows up and is the example that surrounds him is for his healthy development.
On the tables of obese children, sausages are up to half more often on the table than in families with normal-weight children.
More than 19 per cent of the overweight children had on the day before of the clearing-up action under the slogan “adiposity is no coincidence ” Pommes to supper.
In families with big kids, sports are not one of their favourite pastimes, although this also applies to the majority of today ’ s pupils – only 15 percent answered that their parents find time for active exercise at least once a week.
Survey among 900 children
The survey took place last year towards the end of the school year, with nearly 900 children from primary schools all over the Czech Republic being interviewed.
This was already the second year of the campaign "Obesity is not a coincidence", which is supported by the General Health Insurance and the Unilever company.
So far more than 12 thousand pupils from 4th and 8th grades have participated in the project.
Unhealthy diet and a lack of exercise in the family are the decisive factors responsible for the alarmingly increasing number of children who are overweight or even obese.
"Only half of the children surveyed, for example, stated that eating supper five times a day in the mode of breakfast" second breakfast "lunch" dinner "- one of the main requirements for a healthy diet", is one of the results of the survey.
No breakfast and sausage for dinner
Experts point out that also relative little things, as for example also the regular breakfast time of the family, are important for the healthy development of a child.
In the Czech Republic, however, only 23 percent of the students ’ families have breakfast.
And - in most families everyone has their own breakfast.
Worst of all was the finding that in every tenth family there is no breakfast at all.
Breakfast is considered the cornerstone of a healthy daily diet.
The survey showed, among other things, that families of overweight children often consume unhealthy fries.
And almost everyone - regardless of weight - drinks sweet lemonades every day (70 percent)
More than 40 percent of the children surveyed do sports, but only less than half of their parents do so - namely only 15 percent.
Create your own menu
Another part of the survey enabled selected children (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) to compile their own menu based on their appetite and opinion.
"What Czech children between 12 and 15 prefer in terms of nutrition is far from the ideal of a healthy diet.
Among her favourite dishes were many pastries, meat dishes and, of course, desserts.
"Alarming is above all the great popularity of sweet lemonades", is emphasized in the final report of this survey.
At lunch, the main course, the pasta won just before poultry.
The children did not like legumes at all and also the popularity of fish and vegetable dishes as lunch was very low.
Return to health
At the same time, the survey also showed that the children are quite willing to change their eating habits if they get the right information.
"In many cases, the control group of respondents who completed the questionnaire after completing the explanatory lecture" Obesity is not a coincidence "showed a significant shift in preferences towards principles of healthy eating", the results of the project state.
This was evident, for example, in the case of sweet limos, where many children began to give priority to ordinary water.
In the questionnaire, the children also crossed poultry or fish much more often as the main course of the day and were prepared to eat less dumplings or sweet food.
Professionals claim - a stylist must also be a good psychologist
In the introductory article about how stylists learn, I complained a bit that it was a bit too much stuff to start with.
Then I had no idea what was to come.
Lectures by three professionals from the industry, the clothing of problematic figures and a seminar on how the "on the pitch" works.
It is to come still worse.
The closer the examination gets, the more information and practical tasks await us.
But even if the course takes place every Saturday and Sunday, it is still fully booked.
This time we discussed with Director Alena (not a single man takes part in the course) how to attract a woman who does not have an ideally proportioned figure.
And these are, after all, most of us.
Some have a too short neck, others a too boyish figure without proper curves and still others are chubby.
It is up to the stylist to hide broad shoulders visually, to lengthen the neck or to conjure up the necessary curves.
We also got tips on how to dress a type of woman like Jennifer Lopez - i.e. with a big bosom, wide hips and a narrow waist - nicely and figure-hugging, without being too provocative.
For example, if the difference between waist and hips is so big that the skirt or pants really don ’ t fit, you should have at least one piece tailored.
You will certainly not regret that, because well-fitting clothes are simply priceless.
In such a tailor-made skirt, one feels much better than in an off-the-peg skirt, which always slips up and down, stands out in the waist, etc.
In turn, boyish figures can allow themselves to wear clothes with folds, little balls, appliqués, embroidery or gathering.
With this amount of information and figure types I am glad that I have a whole week to let everything go through my head thoroughly.
And yet, I am afraid that, given the homework assigned, it is almost impossible.
Each of the course participants was assigned a celebrity, for whom she should think up suitable outfits - day wear and evening gowns.
We should consider the current appearance, the fashion style of the corresponding star and its type of figure.
I am supposed to "attract" Miranda Kerr, whom you may know from the Victoria's Secret campaign.
Internally, I ’ m cheering, because that ’ s much better for me personally than putting on Britney Spears or Christina Aguilera, for example, who has probably gained about a hundred kilos lately (well, that ’ s a bit exaggerated), or even the young Selena Gomez.
We should cut the garments out of magazines or search on the Internet, print them and then process them graphically.
The "moodboard", as the whole result is called, is supposed to express our very personal style and our relationship to the graphic design.
It is very important to think about the graphic side of the styling.
The stylist not only attracts the models physically, but also creates the so-called product page in the journals (according to specific specifications, for example, trend, handbags, coats, etc.).
Stylist and designer Mario Kameník told us about that.
But only on Sunday.
This means that a stylist must have a good overview.
The Saturday lecture, filled with information on figure types, was spiced by three visitors from the industry:
by stylist Jan Pokorný, fashion designer Jakub Polanka and fashion photographer Ben Renč.
Jakub reminded us that fashion is illusion and that a stylist should be able to exploit it.
And sent in stylist can work with a single piece of clothing in very different ways.
The magic word is variability.
For example, you can wear a trench coat over your jeans as usual, i.e., like a tee shirt or coat, but you can also wear it on your naked body, put on heel shoes and wear it as a dress.
It is enough to roll up the sleeves or the collar and the whole look looks completely different.
"Play with it," he stressed.
But the most convenient advice was: "First you have to know the rules perfectly."
"Only then can you hurt them," said Jakub.
I finally understand why we have to work on all these theories, what you can combine with what and why, even if you often see something completely different in fashion journals.
Not to mention fashion shows.
Thanks to the photographer Ben, I now know that a stylist must have prepared many more clothing variations than he finally photographs.
So for a fashion story with ten pages (or ten outfits) you have to be prepared to style at least fifteen.
And also that the clothing on the photo in combination with other accessories sometimes looks very different than in reality.
With all this you have to expect when designing the outfit.
Jan Pokorný also confirmed that image and style make up half of our success.
You only need to look at Madonna, a not exactly brilliant singer, from whom image and marketing have made a world star.
In the Czech Republic the services of a stylist are rather reserved.
Also well-known personalities often regard this as thrown out money (the main thing is that I bring something, how I look thereby is secondary).
And if one of us can already be styled, then we should expect that he or she will most likely impose a completely different (smaller) size on us than he or she actually needs.
Then you only need to google afterwards, to determine with certainty, that the tabloid press writes, the corresponding celebrity has again closed or decreased, etc.
Jan and Mario advised us on Sunday not to believe that a stylist only needs to focus on fashion and then "assemble" the outfit.
In his work, he must above all communicate with the people he styles and he must be a skilled psychologist.
Assess people without bowing to them and stand by their opinion.
"If any manager orders us to sift through her wardrobe and add beautiful pieces, we can't clear out the whole closet and tell her - my god, that's terrible."
"You have to find at least a few praiseworthy things to which you recommend what you can wear," says Mario.
He also showed us quite concretely what a so-called "place bag" must contain.
In other words, a bag that you close at the waist and in which you carry all the necessary proprietary items with you.
Apart from such clear things as scissors, hair-removal dispensers or safety pins, it also contains such utensils as a nylon thread (this helps the stylist to take pictures of products such as handbags or hats), special clips with which the clothing is gathered at the back if it is too large (pins or other clamps are prohibited so that the fabric does not break) and, of course, sewing utensils.
So that we not only have to listen, but also can try something practical, we learned how to glue shoes correctly.
Even when photographing in the studio, where the floor is flat, you can damage the shoe sole, let alone the one outside.
We glued and glued ourselves o...
You must not even touch the shoes with scissors, so that they are not damaged.
So you have to be really clever.
Mario delighted me by praising my "creation" without reservations.
The aforementioned dexterity is not my strength.
All this was only a fraction of what we got to hear on the second weekend.
One thing has become clear to me in the meantime - to dedicate oneself to styling on a professional level is no child's play.
V Need for Speed: "The Run" - the illegal race across America
Review
The originally carefree journey becomes an early shift due to a series of completely avoidable, amateurish errors.
It succeeded in fulfilling the ambitions to a large extent, but what use is that, if obviously nobody wanted to do a little more.
Even before it reached the counter, the new part with the subtitle "The Run" raised high expectations.
After all, he promised to move the already old game series "Need for Speed" into a new dimension and in the playable demonstration examples he actually seemed to be not only one of many action, but also one of many racing games.
We were also curious about how the fitting passages would turn out, in which the main protagonist gets out of the car and continues on foot.
But as you are used to it with NFS, in the end a lot is different than you expected.
Sure - they are potentially quite decent arcade races, but overall the game is diminished by some unnecessary mistakes that have been present in this series for more or less a few years.
So these are actually no more mistakes, but rather signs of a basically incomprehensible laziness of the game developers.
The adventure starts very well.
First, one is introduced to the story, whose main character Jack has certain problems of a personal nature; the only solution seems to be to take part in an illegal race across America.
In San Francisco, i.e. on the West Coast, people sit at the wheel - with the task of being the first in New York.
The basic idea contains a number of interesting elements.
The entire route is divided into ten stages and more than fifty individual races.
This means that each race is held on a different course and that the individual stages take place in a different, sufficiently different and interesting environment.
You never get the impression that game would always offer the same thing.
Some environments are also very nice to look at, although the technical level of the graphics does not go beyond that of the earlier parts of the series.
So nothing earthshaking.
But the ride through the desert, through autumnal landscape or high up through deeply snow-covered landscape looks visually very pleasant.
Every now and then atypical elements bring a little variety to the individual races.
In the desert, for example, you will be surprised by a desert storm that severely restricts visibility.
In the mountains, on the other hand, you have to be very careful not to be buried by an avalanche.
Besides, the individual races are built in quite well in a row.
Only a few, but they are enough.
For a while you try to overtake the prescribed number of opponents (in principle a classic race), then you have time to catch up (classic race against the stopwatch), then expect a personal duel with a single opponent.
And in addition, the police interfere, who want to screw up the whole thing.
A novelty are passages in which Jack leaves the car.
This is more about certain interactive animations in which Jack flees from someone and where the player has to help him by pressing the right button at the right moment.
So nothing complicated.
It is surprising, however, that there are far fewer such passages in the game than one would expect (concretely only three).
In the end, this is more to the advantage of the game, because at least this element has no chance to get boring - in the context of the above mentioned it belongs to the elements that make the game more varied.
The model strides in the footsteps of the previous parts.
That is to say, seen from today's point of view, it does not tear up trees, but on the other hand one could not claim it would be bad.
If you are looking for realistic simulations, look elsewhere.
But for an action-packed racing driver, the local model will continue to do quite well, although you could find better in the competition.
Until then, everything is in perfect order.
Real problems only appear after a certain period of time.
In contrast to the driving model, the collision model is not completely OK
A game of this kind can hardly be expected to calculate complicated deformations and collisions, but if you have practically no idea how the car behaves before hitting any object, then obviously not everything is in order.
Typical example: When overtaking or driving past oncoming cars, one "grazes" the other car only slightly in some places, but in other, almost identical situations one gets into a catapult and turns wild pirouettes.
Or the cart goes straight to scrap metal.
Thanks to the restart of the system does not matter, ab annoying it is certainly.
The re-arts are solved like this: if you have total damage or land far away from the track, then the game throws you back to the last clue of the track.
Only - in each race you have only five restarts.
When you have exhausted it, everything starts again..
The re-arts are more like a tool, in case something doesn ’ t work, but you shouldn ’ t rely on that.
Sometimes, however, not even the restart helps, because nothing else helps than to learn the critical section from the head.
It is extremely unpleasant that the same things often happen in the same places.
For example, you have to drive through some curves in a very specific way, otherwise you simply do not fit through.
Elsewhere, you will always encounter "civilian" cars in the same configuration, regardless of whether you arrive first or fifth, five seconds earlier or a minute later.
This is particularly annoying in situations when you see that the opponent passes two oncoming cars in front of you, but by the time you get there yourself, the cars are already in such a position that you have to drive around or brake them.
And it does not matter when you arrive there, because everything is designed so that it comes to this situation always close to your nose.
The counterparties have other advantages.
Throughout the game there are a few places where you are always overtaken by the same opponent at the same place and here again regardless of the time.
This is craziest at the end of the game on the long bridge you pass in the opposite direction.
The opponent obviously has to overtake you.
And when he is in front of you, he of course takes the view, so that you can drive your own car in Klump a few times at the beginning.
Sure - you just want to make the game more thrilling and exciting, but this intention is so clear that it quickly spoils your enjoyment of the game.
And that's a pity, because despite the simpler driving model, the game is quite entertaining and sometimes so action-packed that you almost no longer know where the head is.
And in principle, it doesn't matter what's "to blame" for it - the concept of fifty unique routes, the layout of the races in such a way as to avoid boredom, or something completely different...
An unusual idea is also the car change during the races.
One must not overlook the gas stations at the route, because it is here that one can change the car, although in most cases the car that one has is sufficient.
The cars are divided into three categories.
The sports cars are well suited for urban areas, the strong American limousines for the straight highways and exotic super sports cars for technical journeys, for example on the serpentines in the mountains.
Hand in hand with the mode of game history also goes the tasks of the mode (challenges) - thus the races in the individual localities, which one knows from the history.
Here there are not only medals, but also experience points for the own profile to win, which is together for the tasks (challenges) and the history.
In order to reach the higher driver level, various objects must be unlocked: from the car to the backgrounds for the profile.
This is simultaneously associated with the online function Autolog, which compares, among other things, the own achieved results with those of other players and also provides for other collective functions.
One of the other incomprehensible carvers is a situation in the last race of history.
Here you get namely by car in a subway "tunnel" (meinetwegen), where you race in the dark on the rails long (meinetwegen).
On the speedometer, numbers between 150 and 200 km / h (because of me) look, but there comes all at once from behind a subway and drives one uncompromisingly to scrap metal.
In our editorial office we will probably argue for a long time about whether this was a blackout of the game designers or whether the authors think we are so stupid.
The technical side is nothing overwhelming but at least the visual overall impression is in most cases quite appealing and here and there even brilliant.
This makes it all the more annoying that at some exciting moments the refresh rate slows down and this is sometimes quite dramatic.
That concerns however in particular the accidents with larger number of involved ones, where a continuous FPS does not profit one anyway.
Sound reproduction is OK so far and the soundtrack is a matter of taste.
In an effort to appeal to such a broad as possible range of rather young audiences, a soundtrack was created a lá "something from everyone" - but who buys such a game because of the music?!
The general impression of Need for Speed: The Run? The feelings are mixed.
If the game were not diminished by the mentioned totally unnecessary mistakes, we could have said with the phatt of conviction that The Run is the best piece of NFS in the last years.
But so the game seems somehow unfinished.
A great pleasure in itself, but you should be prepared for these mistakes with the power of airport headlights to stand out in the eye.
Concert of "Students of the Velvet Revolution" with singing ensembles of the Charles University
For the third time, the Festa Academica festival offers the combination of World Students Day with the anniversary of the Velvet Revolution, including a musical experience.
In the course of the festival about twenty professional and university choirs present themselves.
The festival will focus on the two concerts that will take place on 17 November.
"The Charles University has a large part in the festival."
"The participants include the choir of the Faculty of Education and the Faculty of Humanities Studies, and the festival committee includes the Rector Václav Hampl," said Jakub Čaloun, head of the organisation team.
The absolute highlight of the festival is the public concert of professional school choirs, which will take place on 17 November from 2 p.m. on the square in front of the National Technical Library in Dejvice.
The programme includes a composition by the great Czech jazz player Karel Růžička "Celebration Jazz Mass".
In the evenings, a concert entitled "Students of the Velvet Revolution" will be held in the gala rooms of the People's House in Vinohrady. Choirs from the Charles University will also perform.
Festa Academica aims not only to celebrate World Student Day with dignity and to commemorate the 22nd anniversary of the Velvet Revolution, but also to present choral music at the highest level to the public and to promote the creative cooperation of young people.
The main organizer is the Czech Choir Association in cooperation with the Johannes Kepler Gymnasium.
The event was held under the patronage of Bohuslav Svoboda, Mayor of Prague and Václav Hampl, Rector of Charles University.
The festival will take place from 16 to 20 November in Prague and Pardubice.
The schedule includes, besides festival concerts, numerous musical meetings, student happenings, matinees and other events.
Detailed information can be found on the festival website www.festaacademica.cz
EU Ambassador Vicenová:
The Czechs have the reputation of negativists and Eurosceptics
"The Lisbon Treaty has noticeably upset the balance between the various institutions."
I did not expect such a hard war to break out. "
"It will take five or six years for the waves to calm down and for everyone to get used to their new role," said Milena Vicenová, the Czech Ambassador to the European Union, when she began her keenly speaking at the Faculty of Law.
Already in the first part of her lecture, in which she succeeded in describing the individual bodies of the EU and their mutual relations in such a clear and comprehensible way that many a lecturer of the Faculty of Law of the Charles University could have envied her, she showed how seriously she takes the motto "understandable and open about Europe".
Ms Vicenová also praised the new permanent President of the Council of Europe, Herman Van Rompuy:
"At first there was criticism that he was too inconspicuous - a gray official who could not cope with such a role, but I have to say it took everyone's breath away how well he took care of the matter.
"He is a person who manages to listen patiently to twenty-seven member states, to communicate with them and, above all, has clear ideas about how the EU should proceed.
She then explained the new position of the High Representative for Foreign Affairs and Security Policy as an answer to the question: Who is this actually - the European Union? Which number should I call? ", i.e. as an important step towards agreement and better readability of the EU's policy towards states such as China or India.
Nobody wants to forbid us our oil cap toppings
Mrs Vicenová also addressed the agenda according to which the European Union lived, lives and intends to live in the near future.
She described the Czech Presidency of two years ago as a success.
The Czechs had overcome the financial crisis and the gas crisis and also organised the Eastern Partnership Summit.
She described the case of the government during the Presidency as a major negative factor which had severely damaged the image of the Czech Republic.
The Czech representation in the EU currently has its hands full.
In the words of the Ambassador, things were quite hectic not only with the Presidency, but also with the ensuing crisis, which has not yet been overcome.
And the EU ’ s Seven Year Budget still has to be approved, which makes matters much more complicated precisely because of the current economic situation.
Whether it will be a lean and thrifty budget, which sectors will be prioritised, which countries will receive more and which less support, all this is now on the agenda.
The Ambassador also recalls her own slogans with which she came to Brussels: 'Understandable about Europe'.
"If I don't like something, it's greyish abbreviations, foreign words and jargon that nobody understands.
As a citizen, how am I supposed to know whether people in Brussels really think up crooked or round cucumbers and bananas of different sizes, or whether someone really wants to ban us from toppings?
It would also have liked to use EU soil to get more Czechs into European institutions.
A two- or multi-speed Europe in prospect
According to the EU ambassador, the Czechs have a reputation for being Eurosceptics, who perceive the negative rather than the positive sides of the matter.
All the more annoying is the weak representation of Czechs in European institutions.
Many factors are to blame, including the reluctance of our candidates, their inability to write motivation letters and, last but not least, the weak support of the Czech side.
In addition to the successful Czech presidency, she also highlighted the strength and cooperation of the V4 group.
"Believe me, if a Pole or Hungarian comes to me and a Slovak is nearby, then the Frenchman next to me says:" Hey, what are you sticking your heads together - is that your V4 again? "and yet makes a pretty sour face.
According to Vicenové, the EU expects tough rules for the budget policies of the member states in the future.
It regards the concept of a two-speed Europe as much more real than a 'European federation'.
"We have here the countries of the euro area and the countries outside the euro area.
"We have the Schengen area and we already have the Institute of Enhanced Cooperation."
"For the first time it has been said that only those countries which want to should cooperate and that those which do not want to do so should stand on the sidelines."
"There will be more and more such institutions, which will ultimately lead to a strong 'multi-speed Europe'", expects Ms Vicenová.
In this regard, she also praised the role of the Czech Republic and Herman Van Rompuyes in enforcing the principle that all issues affecting the entire EU must be discussed by all member states and not only by the eurozone countries.
Brand story:
The innovator IBM enters the second century of its existence
If one wanted to search for a suitable word that characterizes IBM's strategy the most precisely, then this would probably be the word "longevity".
For the general public, IBM is synonymous with technological revolution, known as a modern enterprise, although a century has passed since its inception.
Her first boss - the visionary Thomas J. Watson senior - laid the foundation for this longevity.
Already he advocated the slogan that countless global problems could be easily solved if people were willing to think a bit.
His slogan "Think!" thus became a trademark around which the life of the future giant was to take place (and at the same time the title of the company magazine, which IBM began to publish in 1935).
This was also the basis of the corporate culture thoroughly prepared by Watsen.
"For us at IBM, this long-term thinking means a continuous movement towards the future.
IBM survived and was successful for an entire century, also because it remained true to its principles and did not shrink from changing everything else around it.
This allowed us, during the first century, to transform technologies, business and society.
We hope to achieve even more in the next hundred years, "said Samuel J. Palmisano, the current director of the company on the occasion of the anniversary.
Smart system
As early as the 1930s, Watson was already providing social care for his employees – in a similar way to the entrepreneur Baťa in Czechoslovakia: IBM ’ s people were one of the first American employees to have paid vacation, be insured by the entrepreneur plus elegant uniforms as work clothes, and have a thoughtful remuneration system for the best innovators and traders.
IBM's long-term relationships with its customers are equally sophisticated.
From the outset, the company was ingenious at promoting talent - IBM was one of the first companies in the world to eliminate all discrimination - and was able to choose accordingly.
In line with this anti-discrimination strategy is also the current plan that will alternate Palmisan at the head of IBM next year by a woman - by Virginia Rometty.
She has been with IBM for thirty years and has held the position of Head of Sales, Marketing and Strategy.
In recent years, IBM has been conducting so-called online brainstorming sessions, from which many future strategies and innovations have arisen.
No wonder - there are enough ideas, the company employs almost half a million people.
An institution with a good reputation
Their unshakable position in the business guarantees a strong image for the company, both internally and externally.
"From the beginning, IBM has had the concept of an institution rather than a mere technology company," said Harvard Business School professor and author of a book on IBM, Rosabeth Moss Kanter.
"IBM is not a technology company, but a company that helps solve business problems using technology," George Colony of Consulting, Forrester Research, added.
As the company itself points out, it makes a difference to be only present on the market or to shape it directly through this presence.
IBM - in the states of their logo called familiarly "Big Blue", has grown in a century to one of the largest companies in the world.
It is one of the most versatile technology companies ever - IBM develops hardware and software, infrastructure, hosting and consulting services in an incredible product range - from servers to nanotechnology.
Of all American technology companies, IBM holds the most patents, and five of its employees have been awarded the Nobel Prize.
His most famous inventions include ATMs, credit cards, financial swap, barcodes and even diskettes.
With a market capitalization of about 220 billion dollars, IBM was the second largest technology company (after Apple) this year, overtaking Microsoft for the first time since 1996.
Looking Ahead
Not all products and innovations met the taste of the customers of today - unfortunate were for example the attempt with the own operating system OS / 2, the on-line ¼ service Prodigy or also the computers IBM PC jr.
"Business is based on moving forward, so one must not bind oneself emotionally to the past," says Samuel J. Palmisano.
Therefore IBM has no problem to build its foundations on different platforms - and if they don't work, to leave them again.
Contrary to the opponent Microsoft, which stands and falls in principle with its operating system Windows.
Promising technologies
Services, software and hardware each contribute a fifth to the profits of IBM.
Even in 1990, hardware was represented most strongly with a share of more than fifty percent.
Since 2000, IBM has sold little profit-generating assets worth $15 billion, but invested $58 billion at the same time in technology purchases.
In these investments, IBM continues after 2008, when the modern financial crisis swept the world like a storm for the first time.
Here, too, IBM remained faithful to the legacy of its first boss, Thomas J. Watson, who increased investment in the midst of the Great Depression.
So far it seems that the company IBM survives today's crisis unscathed.
The value of IBM ’ s equities has skyrocketed by 120 percent since 2008, and the company ’ s net profit continues to grow.
The company slogan of IBM is: everything can be changed - except the values.
This is another reason to expect this flexible giant to master the next crisis.
IBM History: From Cheese Slicer to World Flights
IBM (International Business Machines), founded one hundred years ago in New York, initially had a rather complicated name - Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
It took the name IBM only in 1924 - originally it was about a brand name for a branch in Canada and South America.
The foundation stone for the later company IBM was laid by the merger of four companies whose history dates back to the 1980s of the 19th century.
They possessed technologies such as the famous puncture card watches for registering the start and end of work.
Charles Ranlett Flint, who also served as Chairman of the Supervisory Board until 1930, became the architect of this new company.
And it was Flint who hired the head of the rival company, Thomas J. Watson, to help him run the company.
This leader then outshone even the founders of IBM - based on Watson's ideas to this day the invincible culture and identity of the company.
Watson ran the company until 1952.
IBM, as the name suggests, began with the production and sale of all kinds of machines for trade - from sausages and cheese slicers to checkout counters.
In the first four decades of running the company, Watson doubled its sales to nine million dollars, and the company gradually expanded to all continents.
Watson was so indispensable for the company that he sat in the executive chair for forty years, only then was he replaced by his son, Thomas Watson Junior.
Under his leadership, IBM began working on the development of artificial intelligence and also developed the first programming language.
In the 1960s, technicians and computers from IBM helped NASA direct flights into space - to Mercury and Saturn, and in 1969 also the famous flight of man to the moon.
In 1964 IBM developed the first computer family with the same architecture - the series IBM System / 360.
A classic PC, which was the computer standard at that time, was launched in 1981 under the name IBM 5150.
Twenty years later IBM sold its computer production to the Chinese company Lenovo, but on the other hand it bought the consultancy part of the PricewaterhouseCoopers company and thereby entered fully into the business of consulting services and services with high added value.
The strategy that has paid off for IBM over the past three years is the "Smarter Planet" concept.
It embodies the intention to use technology wisely in areas not even planned so far, for example to improve the situation in transport and in city management.
In the retail sector, IBM recently launched the Smarter Commerce platform to help retailers manage the entire commercial cycle.
IBM also has a strong history in the Czech Republic.
As early as 1932, IBM founded a branch in what was then Czechoslovakia - the first country in Central and Eastern Europe.
Today, IBM ČR also operates a strategic outsourcing center in Brno.
The Headquarters for Central and Eastern Europe is located in Prague, which is also home to a world-class research team dealing with voice recognition technology.
