Development of travel prices since 1989
Until 1989 there were only five authorised state travel agencies in the former Czechoslovakia: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
The travel agencies sold at that time above all only journeys into the socialist Eastern bloc countries, to the west at that time only selected ones were allowed.
And so Czech tourists travelled to the Baltic Sea (to the German Democratic Republic - the GDR), to the Soviet Union (Sochi on the Crimean peninsula on the Black Sea), to Bulgaria and Romania to the Black Sea and to Hungary at the Balaton.
A clear exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when one was allowed to travel to Yugoslavia, then Yugoslavia took a pro-Western course and therefore the trips to Yugoslavia were severely restricted.
A great paradox of those socialist times was that not even citizens of the Eastern Bloc (including the Czechoslovakians) were allowed to travel freely within the framework of the socialist countries.
For example, if a citizen of the Czechoslovak Republic wanted to travel individually to Poland or even to the Soviet Union, he or she would need a so-called invitation letter, otherwise individual travel was not possible.
Already at that time the travel agencies offered also journeys into the west, then one had to take however gigantic queues into account or also overnight in the sleeping bag before the travel agency, and / or have at least "good acquaintances" in the travel agency.
Even so, the matter was far from over.
The so-called foreign currency promise - the condition for an exit to the West - was only given to "politically reliable" people - the others were not allowed to travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely exchangeable currency, so without the promise of foreign currency it would have been impossible to find the necessary financial resources (Western currency) for a trip to the West.
The vast majority of Czechs spent their holidays inland, so it is no wonder that the Czechs bought countless weekend cottages and dacha - a habit that continues to this day.
The Velvet Revolution of 1989 was followed by a Czechs travel revolution.
While until 1989 holidays in the GDR or Bulgaria were the measure of all things, last year the Czechs spent 4.5 million of their holidays abroad in countries all over the world.
A huge paradox, of which one is not even aware today, is the fact that one could not travel to the currently most popular holiday country of the Czechs - Croatia at all until 1989, because it was part of the former Yugoslavia.
Right from the beginning of the 90s of the last century, the foreign exchange obligation was lifted in the neighboring Western European countries, which caused a huge wave of short visits, especially to Vienna in Austria and Germany.
For a long time the Czechoslovakians simply could not get enough of their trips to the West, everyone wanted to have been there at least for a few days.
During their trips to Paris, the Czech holidaymakers slept in a tent in the park, because who would have had the money for accommodation in a hotel or pension back then.
A typical feature of trips by Czechs abroad was a trunk packed with canned goods, beer and dried sausages etc.
Another important milestone was the introduction of the freely exchangeable Czech Koruna - after decades our tourists were finally able to buy the Western currency freely.
Our standard of living and, as a result, our average salaries rose, which led to another important moment in 1997.
Due to increased demand for travel, travel agencies began preparing regular charter flights after 1997, making air travel incredibly cheaper than in the past, thanks to the ability to negotiate volume discounts.
At the end of the 1990s the Czechs, with the exception of the USA, already had currency-free payments with all the highly developed countries of the world, which made travelling even easier.
Another interesting moment in the history of the "post" velvet tourism came in 2000, when due to high demand the first direct charter flight to an exotic country - Thailand - was handled.
Since then, direct charter flights with Czech passengers have been flying to distant sunny countries every year; this year twelve exotic destinations are being served directly from the Czech Republic.
About 100 thousand Czechs travel to exotic countries every year!
Another significant moment in the epoch that marked our "post-revolutionary" development came in 2008.
On 17 November 2008, the USA lifted the visa requirement for Czech tourists, making our country definitely one of the most developed countries in the world.
In 2008, for the first time, the Czechs spent more than half of their holiday abroad (50.3%) and for the first time in their history, they spent more than CZK 15 thousand per capita on a single holiday including the cost of the resort.
The general meeting is to find a new chairman - again a stalemate threatens.
For almost five months, Czech football has had no chairman, and there is a risk that the successor to Ivan Hašek at the head of the Czech Football Federation (FAČR) will not be known even after the extraordinary general meeting in Nymburk on Thursday.
To date, no agreement has been reached on the rules governing elections.
And without them, no vote at all on the three potential successors is possible.
Three interested parties want to manage the Czech football - Jindřich Rajchl, Miroslav Pelta and Tomáš Paclík.
In June, Hašek resigned from his position, urging his colleagues to come to an agreement and find a strong personality to lead football in the future.
But in the post-Hašek era, the old quarrels between the two chambers of the association broke out again, and they could not agree on a common candidate.
This was made abundantly clear on 16 September, when the new chairman was to be selected.
The delegates of the Annual General Meeting came to the People ’ s House in the Smíchov district of Prague for free, because the negotiations did not lead to any result and it was not only about the election itself.
It was not even possible to agree on who was actually entitled to vote at the plenary - only the statutory representatives or even the functionaries with a power of attorney.
Agreement was reached, at least in part, on this single point, helped by the recommendation of the Institute of State and Law, which considers that representation on a power of attorney basis is not permitted.
Disputes over the election rules continue, however.
Nor did the Executive Committee shed any light on the matter, at whose meetings - whether ordinary or extraordinary - there is nothing else on the agenda in principle.
Even if views on the election changed a few times, the neuralgic point remained the same.
The question is: what should be done in the third round to avoid a stalemate?
Dušan Svoboda, one of the three vice-chairmen of FAČR, who represents professional football in the management, stated: "The issue is whether to proceed in accordance with the statutes or whether to find a completely different model."
According to the statutory model, in the third round, the candidate who receives the greater percentage support in the chamber for which he is standing for election wins.
Moravia is supposedly prepared to accept the compromise that the candidate receiving the higher number of votes from both chambers should win.
The Czech side insists on the condition that the winner receives at least a two-thirds majority in this percentage vote count.
"Then the two preliminary rounds will no longer make sense at all, this method would call the entire bicameral concept into question", Svoboda understands the objections of the Moravian side, which would find it best not to bend the election regulations, but to vote according to the valid statutes.
Surprisingly, Tomáš Paclík agrees to this, even if it is becoming apparent that the statutory election regulations are the most likely to accommodate Pelta of all candidates.
"It is my wish that as far as possible be elected according to the statutes."
"In order to avoid any unreasonable alternatives, as at the last general meeting," explained owner (of the football club) Victoria Plzeň, who is running for the first time and has distinguished himself from Pelta in his statements.
But Pelta remains optimistic.
In his opinion, the new chairman will be known in Nymburk and he believes that the candidates will also cooperate constructively in the future.
"The possible qualification of the national team for the European Football Championship today would certainly contribute to calm minds."
"When football is on the wave of euphoria, there is a greater willingness to cooperate," says the Jablonec functionary, who has the most experience of all three adepts, both at the professional and regional level.
Rajchl is more reserved.
"I hope to reach an agreement, but the situation is unfortunately ambivalent."
"This is not a matter between the people of Bohemia and Moravia, but there are certain efforts to" straighten out "the regulations for one's own purposes."
"Therefore a further blockage at the Annual General Meeting is not impossible."
"However, I hope that common sense will prevail in the end," Rajchl said.
Only - there is not much time left for the agreement of all sides.
Some negotiations were supposed to take place directly in Montenegro, but who knows whether the football generality will be complete in the run-up to the qualifying match.
The charter plane, with which among others Dalibor Kučera and Rajchl were to fly to Podgorice, could not take off at all in the morning in Prague due to a technical malfunction and so there was a feverish search for a substitute variant, how to bring a part of the executive committee to the venue of the Barrage.
In the end, the meeting at ministerial level, which is supposed to take place on Wednesday, will be crucial.
Josef Dobeš, the Minister for Education, Youth and Physical Education, would have liked to have persuaded the divided parties within the largest sports federation in the country to reach an agreement.
There is a lot at stake: state subsidies, the trustworthiness of Czech football and also the upcoming general meeting of the ČSTV, which is supposed to show the Czech sport the new direction after the financial problems of Sazka.
Paclík goes to fight for the position of chairman because he does not see a suitable candidate
