Europe ’ s Most Beautiful Pools
Jump into the Blue
By Julia Stanek
Paddling pools in Ufo design, magnificent pools in Budapest: If you travel through Europe, you can experience a blue wonder - and relax your tired legs in bubble baths after a city tour or a hike.
A book shows where wellness in the water is most beautiful.
When Iris Meder went on a research trip in the past year and a half, she could not miss one thing in her luggage: her swimsuit.
Lying backwards on the water, she looked up into artistically designed domes, swam towards marble-putti waiting at the edge of the pool, and marveled at meticulously restored Art Nouveau swimming halls.
If she liked a bath, she quickly added it to her notebook - including interesting details about the building's construction and history.
Architecture historian Meder explored more than 200 swimming pools in this way - and now presents them in her recently published book "Badefreuden": Volksschwimmhallen in Munich, historical bathing palaces in the Black Forest, "Hardcore" concrete buildings in the Taunus.
Her "journey to the most extraordinary spas in Central Europe" took her through 13 countries: in addition to Germany, Austria and Switzerland, she visited places in Italy, France, the Czech Republic, Slovakia, Slovenia, Hungary, Romania, Poland - and a city in Luxembourg, Serbia and Croatia.
The 46-year-old German is a true bathing enthusiast.
She doesn ’ t have much to do with sports, says Meder – but it ’ s different in the water.
The only annoying thing is that swimming fans have to resign themselves to blue tiles and chlorine stench, while joggers can inhale the beguiling scent of spruce forests or listen to the cheerful chirping of birds in the park.
"One day I wondered why swimming pools always have to be so ugly," says Meder, who lives in Vienna.
"So I started to collect beautiful baths."
Water surface doubles architecture
Splashing in the diving pool and essential sauna - the wellness factor in baths is so great because all the senses are served, says Meder.
And if the builders have made an effort, swimming pools can be a real feast for the eyes: "Instead of a floor, you have a water surface in baths."
"On the one hand it is transparent, but on the other it reflects the beauty of the entire building."
Everything doubles visually: high vaults, colourful tiles, springboards.
On 190 pages, the small-format illustrated book "Badefreuden" (Bathing Pleasures) conveys interesting facts about the architectural and cultural history of historical wellness and oases - but above all, it makes you want to jump into the blue.
Meder discovered remarkable specimens during her research in Hungary.
In addition to splendid thermal baths such as the 100-year-old Széchenyi Baths in Budapest, she found a nitrate-containing water in a rustic karst cave (Miskolc Cave Spa) and a thermal bath, whose pools are filled with alkaline water and are located in a bottle-shaped building (Városi Termálfürdö in Jászberény).
Many heated outdoor swimming pools in Switzerland and Austria offer spectacular views: While the Zurich Dachbad has the whole city in mind, the outdoor pool of a swimming pool in St. Anton offers a view of the snow-covered Arlberg - and: In the steam bath there is a window from which you can observe the hustle and bustle on the ski slopes.
Perhaps the most unusual pool design awaits bathers in Längenfeld: the Aquadome Ötztal looks like a UFO just landed in the Alps.
In winter, it steams from three bowls open to the sky, while in the background, the mountains of the Ötztal rise into the sky.
Alhambra in the Black Forest
Not in every swimming pool rose the pool. collector Meder the smell of chlorine in the nose.
Many thermal baths smell of sulfur, in the Árpád ’ bath in the Hungarian Békescsaba it stinks so strongly of fuel oil that one hardly believes to have landed in a health bath.
The smell comes from the alkali hydrogen-carbonate-containing healing water, which is almost black and whose silt sticks to your skin as soon as you slide into the pool - a special kind of wellness experience.
In one place, however, Iris Meder was also disappointed in her search for beautiful swimming spots: when she wanted to visit the outdoor and sunbathing in the Czech spa Luhatschowitz, she found a fenced off area.
The spa designed by the architect Dušan Jurkovic in 1902 has since been closed.
When Meder glanced through the weathered windows of the red, white, yellow, Art Nouveau building, she saw weeds growing between the tiles.
The decay was counteracted in an enchanting swimming pool in the Black Forest: the Palais Thermal in Bad Wildbad.
This bath has already passed three construction phases; you can discover not only neo-Romanesque elements dating back to its construction in 1844, but also a Moorish hall in the Alhambra style, which was added around 1900.
Since the careful modernization in 1995, the Palais Thermal is the favorite pool of the pool connoisseur Iris Meder - and not only because she originally comes from the Black Forest.
"It's quite an achievement to merge such different styles into such a great unit," says Meder.
With such a palace the dive in the thermal pool is obviously only secondary.
