21er Haus in Vienna
The Moved Pavilion
By Ingeborg Wiensowski
A history of architecture with ups, downs and happy endings: The Austrian world exhibition pavilion in Brussels won prizes in 1958, became a museum in Vienna, stood empty and dilapidated.
Now it is being reopened as an exhibition venue.
When modern post-war architecture is raved about, about clear forms, glass halls, courageous curves and new building materials, which are typical of the belief in technical progress, then the Austrian pavilion of the architect Karl Schwanzer for the Brussels World Exhibition in 1958 is an apt and famous example.
At that time, Schwanzer's pavilion was awarded the Grand Prix d'Architecture for its light and floating steel, the glass construction.
The building is still considered a milestone in contemporary architecture.
He made the architect so famous that he also built Austria ’ s pavilion at the next world exhibition.
In 1973, he finally became internationally famous with his legendary four-cylinder BMW plus bowl-like extension in Munich.
His pavilion, which was planned as a temporary exhibition building, was erected after the World Exhibition in the Swiss Garden at Vienna ’ s Südbahnhof station, rebuilt and opened in 1962 as a museum of the 20th century – the “House of the Twenties ”.
But the building was not suitable as a spatial and technical museum - no walls for hanging art, no good climate.
Nevertheless, it was used until the contemporary art in Vienna got a new house.
Since 2001, the building stood empty and came down more and more.
Now the architect Adolf Krischanitz has rebuilt the pavilion, which is now called "21er Haus" and will in future be used as a museum for contemporary art.
On Tuesday evening, the Belvedere Museum, to which the building belongs, opens the first exhibition there - a stroke of luck in every respect.
In 2007, Agnes Husslein became the new director of the Österreichische Galerie Belvedere.
She earned her doctorate in art history with a remarkable career in her youth as a figure skater, later at Sotheby ’ s, the Guggenheim Museum, and as the founding director of the Museum der Moderne Salzburg. She pushed through the renovation with politicians and conservationists, obtained public funds and private sponsors, and determined the use of the building.
In addition to contemporary art, the works of the sculptor Fritz Wotruba were to be exhibited by the foundation of the same name, there was to be a café and a bookshop, and an office building had to be built for this purpose.
Strict supervision, small budget
Krischanitz was the ideal cast for the performance.
Not only because he sensitively converted and expanded Joseph Olbrichs Secession in Vienna and won the competition, but also because he studied with Schwanzer at the Technical University of Vienna and the pavilion was a "tremendously important place" for him, where he had seen the exhibitions "almost every weekend".
He knew the original design, and he knew the problems of the building, which lost its generosity and lightness when it was moved to Vienna and converted.
There were far greater problems with the current conversion: the building was "an energy centrifuge", says Krischanitz.
The window profiles of the glass façade were replaced, glass fibre reinforced insulating glass was used and the glass roof was replaced by special safety glass.
Cold bridges ， steel beams have been reinforced or replaced, and asbestos-filled ceilings have been rehabilitated.
Two basements provided space for the new use, a lowered light trench between the house and the street provides the lighting, a bridge leads to the entrance - almost a new building, but still the light Schwanzer pavilion.
The original exterior doors have remained, the house is painted in the old rust-brown color.
And the cinema hall is even exactly as it used to be.
And all this under strict supervision of the monument authority and with a small budget.
"Often a material had to be found that is good and cheap and that the office of monument protection liked," says Krischanitz, pointing to a rough ground in the basement.
Despite all the constraints, problems and alterations, the building has remained flexible and light.
It was difficult with the pavilion, "that came from Brussels", Krischanitz has recently said, a typical "Drop in the city history".
Such an architecture stands "always in the wrong place" and nevertheless wants to "awaken a real consciousness".
In this case, however, the 21er Haus is not in the wrong place, because an urban development stroke of luck has occurred: around the Swiss garden, the completely redesigned "Hauptbahnhofsquartier" with office and residential buildings is under construction.
And another stroke of luck may yet occur: the 21er Haus could receive reinforcement from another Krischanitz building, because the collector Francesca von Habsburg has bought the Temporäre Kunsthalle in Berlin, and one hears that she is already negotiating with the city for a neighbourly location in the Swiss Garden.
