"UBS has achieved the turnaround".
"I am looking forward to working with Kaspar Villiger and Oswald Grübel".
But as early as September, it became clear that everything would be very different.
A UBS dealer in London had bypassed all of the bank ’ s security systems and gambled around €1.7 billion.
UBS ’ s CEO Oswald Grübel, a famous banker not only in Switzerland, had to leave.
Since then, the Chairman of the Board of UBS has also been regarded as unwell - and everyone is asking: When will Axel Weber finally arrive?
It has already become known that Weber will be able to advise the Bank from February 2012.
And he will take over the chairmanship of the Board as early as May - not just in 2013, as the Bank announced on Tuesday.
For Axel Weber it will be tough.
He is not a banker, but a professor of economics and a central banker, and would certainly have needed a period of familiarisation.
At a stroke, he assumes responsibility for the strategy of a bank that has just proved once again that it has long since earned the title of 'Europe's largest scandalous bank'.
Because on the one hand UBS is huge - until recently it was the world's largest asset manager - and on the other hand it has been sliding from one scandal to the next for years.
Nothing, it seems, is spared the once so proud Swiss bank.
It began in the financial crisis.
Until 2007, UBS had an excellent reputation.
She had combined the image of the secretive and solid, but also sophisticated Swiss asset manager with ambitious goals: She wanted to become a major player in investment banking.
In 2007, for example, UBS managed $1.6 trillion more money-rich customers than any other bank in the world.
And, on the other hand, it had advanced as an investment bank into the league of the world ’ s largest banks.
That made an impression.
Hans Geiger, a former banker and later a long-standing professor of banking in Zurich, recounts: "At that time I always presented UBS to my students as a model of a good bank."
"From today's point of view, one wonders: How could I be so wrong?"
He was very wrong.
In 2007, it was first revealed that something had gone badly wrong in UBS.
In the middle of the year, CEO Peter Wuffli, who had hitherto been regarded as a highly intellectual and equally brilliant banker, resigned surprisingly.
A few months later, one sensed why he had left.
The investment division of the bank had gambled with subprime and had to write off billions.
To shoulder this burden, UBS announced a CHF13 billion capital increase.
But it did find investors, but some that some would have sniffed at until shortly before: an opaque Asian sovereign wealth fund from Singapore and an Arab sovereign wealth fund that was so secretive that it didn ’ t even get its name.
But that was only the first blow.
In April 2008, things got worse.
The bank had to announce new losses worth billions, and the chairman of the board, Marcel Ospel, who in 2006 was the second-best paid board member in Switzerland, resigned.
The catastrophe followed in October 2008: UBS was on the verge of collapse and had to be saved by the state due to its bad investments in the financial crisis.
The National Bank bought tens of billions of problematic securities from UBS, while the Swiss Confederation paid six billion francs for a compulsory convertible bond, which enabled it to become a co-owner of the bank.
The whole of Switzerland was shocked - because it noticed how dramatic it is for a small country when it hosts such large banks.
After all, UBS ’ s balance sheet total in 2007 was more than five times Switzerland ’ s economic performance (see chart).
"Once again, we could not save UBS," says banking researcher Geiger.
The first disaster was followed by the second.
A few months later, UBS capitulated in a tax dispute with America, agreeing to disclose the data of wealthy clients who may have evaded taxes with the bank ’ s help.
It also agreed to pay $780 million to repay unwarranted profits from these deals, including a penalty.
Thus, UBS more or less openly acknowledged having helped with tax evasion.
At the same time, she lost something that had always been her capital in the competition for rich customers: the aura of secrecy.
After the scandal, Swiss banking secrecy was no longer the same.
This was followed by the resignation of the Chairman and Chairman of the Board of Directors.
And the exodus of customer funds.
Within a few months, the bank had lost credibility in both key areas: investment banking through misguided speculation and asset management through tax evasion assistance.
