And it is becoming obvious that risk management in investment banking is still not working.
“With the Adoboli case, it has become clear that too little has changed in terms of risk control, ” says Martin Janssen, economist and professor of finance at the University of Zurich ’ s banking institute.
The CFO of a major German bank is also certain: "The problem with UBS is that it does not have risk control under control."
Yet it was precisely the idea of caution with which the Swiss bankers long ago set out to become guardians of the world ’ s great fortunes: no too great risks, but security for the money – even beyond the Alpine republic the world might collapse.
The safes of the Swiss banks had become a symbol of unshakable reliability, like Lindt and Sprüngli for particularly fine chocolate.
The head office of UBS in Zurich still fits the cliché of the dignified Swiss private bank - it is just a bit bigger.
The location is classic.
The bank is headquartered on Zurich ’ s Bahnhofstrasse, which leads directly from the main railway station to Lake Zurich, surrounded by the snow-capped peaks of the Swiss mountains.
The buildings here are magnificent, the shop rents are among the highest in Europe.
Jewelers such as Tiffany's can be found here between traditional Swiss shops such as the Confiserie Sprüngli.
Swiss banks have resided here for centuries: from the National Bank and the Palace of Credit Suisse to elite private banks such as Julius Baer.
The reception hall of the UBS is entered through a heavy revolving door.
Inside, the walls are covered with marble, in front of them there are thick leather armchairs, next to the Bench Logo there is a large sign to the "Safe".
UBS knows what the customer is looking for: security.
However, both major Swiss banks, UBS and Credit Suisse, eventually suppressed this idea of the Swiss bank – or betrayed it, as the head of a small Swiss private bank thinks.
He would rather not read his name in the newspaper because, like all Swiss bankers, he also does business with the two big banks.
UBS has become far too big, he finds - especially in investment banking, where the Anglo-Saxons have also spread.
The Swiss would have nothing more to say there.
"And if they do, they have long since adapted to the customs of the Anglo-Saxons."
Indeed, it was Anglo-Saxon investment banking that changed UBS, yielding first big profits and then the debacle: no European financial institution has lost as much money in the subprime jungle as the big Swiss bank.
The disaster became visible on October 15, 2008.
"On that Wednesday, the ruling coalition of the small country of seven million decided on the largest rescue operation in the history of its nation," writes the author Lukas Hässig in his book "The UBS Crash".
The politicians approved up to 68 billion Swiss francs, or around 45 billion euros, in order to rescue the major bank that was about to go bankrupt.
How did this come about?
When talking to Swiss bankers, they see the problem mainly in the size of UBS.
In June 1998, two of the three major Swiss banks merged to form a huge corporation.
A bank was formed that was already too big for small Switzerland at the time of the merger - and continued to grow.
It helped that UBS ’ s two different predecessors complemented each other: a rich but sleepy bank with a focus on wealth management in Zurich, and a poorer but already more internationalized one.
Suddenly, internationalized investment bankers came up with a lot of cheap money to spin a huge wheel.
Two names are associated with the rise of UBS: Peter Wuffli, CEO of UBS from 2001 to 2007, and Marcel Ospel, then Chairman of the Board of Directors.
"I always thought that Wuffli and Ospel were a dream team," says banking researcher Hans Geiger.
"Wuffli, the high-intellectual, modest, who knows a lot about models and statistics, and Ospel, the belly man, who has worked his way up from the banking doctrine to the very top."
But in the end Ospel relied on Wuffli.
And Wuffli probably made a decisive mistake in the end: “He thought that his models were the reality, ” says Geiger.
"This is a tragic case."
Tragically, perhaps.
It is clear: arrogance came before the fall.
UBS employees clearly remember the executives of the meetings at which CEO Wuffli repeatedly gave the same slogan: get Goldman Sachs off the throne.
The American bank was the most powerful investment bank in the world.
She led the League Tables, the rankings that documented the success of the banks of the time.
That is where UBS wanted to go, to the very top.
She had already taken a few steps.
In foreign exchange and stock trading, she played at the top.
However, management consultants who were appointed highlighted a weakness: in the international interest business, in the bankers' language "Fixed Income", there was a huge distance to the largest banks.
UBS has gaps in US mortgage products.
To close this gap, UBS embarked on an adventure that almost cost her her existence.
Hungry for growth, both the bank itself and a pre-established hedge fund invested in American subprime assets.
It became a huge machine, packaging and passing securities on to American mortgage loans, but also retaining risks.
Even when other banks were already looking for an exit.
"Even in the summer of 2007, when the American real estate market was in flames, UBS bought there," says Geiger, a banking expert.
So great is the euphoria, so deep is the fall.
One manager after another had to leave, as the attempts to clean up turned out to be more difficult than expected.
Items at UBS have become ejection seats and remain wobbly to this day.
Whoever now runs the big bank has an almost impossible job.
He must find a strategy for a bank that has lost all the obvious business models.
Banking researcher Geiger already has an idea: No more investment banking, concentration on asset management, return to Swiss roots.
The bank does not want to go that far (yet).
But investment banking is set to shrink sharply, that much is already clear.
Next Thursday, the new bank manager Sergio Ermotti will present his future strategy to the world.
The 51-year-old Italo-Swiss was actually only intended as a temporary solution when the bank surprisingly parted ways with its predecessor Grübel.
In the meantime, he has established himself: he is to run the business of UBS on a permanent basis, the Zurich bank announced on Tuesday.
Ermotti wants the investment bank to go back to the mid-nineties.
He cuts 3500 posts.
But that will not be enough.
UBS needs a vision.
Who is she?
How does she want to make money?
These are the questions that Axel Weber is already asking himself.
So far, he has only publicly said that he and his wife would first look for an apartment in Zurich.
Next year.
