In many places, rooks are regarded as "problem birds". Experts claim that these highly intelligent animals can no longer be driven out of cities.
Some like them, others want to get rid of them very quickly: crows have been part of the cityscape for centuries, but in many municipalities residents complain about the dirt and noise of the animals.
A remedy against the "problem birds" is so far not in view.
Rooks are impossible to get out of the cities, experts said at the first crow symposium in the East Frisian city of Leer.
There specialists from the entire federal territory discussed possible ways out.
You are looking for alternatives in the cities
Conservationists attributed the problems in cities to the rural exodus of the particularly protected rooks: the use of chemicals in agriculture is increasingly destroying traditional habitats.
Hunting, increasing cultivation and the felling of typical breeding trees made life difficult for the birds.
Crows are protected.
Large colonies with more than 600 breeding pairs exist, among others, in the Westphalian Soest, in the northwest, among others, in Jever, Diepholz and Achim near Bremen, as well as in Leer.
In 2005, a controversial project for the mass killing of crows in the county made headlines there.
Critics had described the catching of animals in bird traps and the killing with batons as particularly brutal.
The urban and landscape planner Werner Klöver from Leer has stated: "The normal expulsion, the agitation, is useless."
Splashing nests away with water or felling trees often has undesirable consequences, said environmental expert Manfred Kaiser from Lahr in Baden-Württemberg.
"The animals evade, large colonies split up and spread elsewhere."
Scare is conceivable only as an exception at hospitals, retirement homes or schools.
"We have to live with them, we can't get them away."
Without the surrounding countryside the problem in the cities cannot be solved, meant mayor Wolfgang waiter from empty.
A combination of agitating the animals from sensitive living areas and attraction offers is conceivable, in order to settle them in other places again.
In contrast, psychologist and ethnologist Uta Maria Jürgens called for "information boards instead of chainsaws" in order to treat animals in a completely different way: "After all, we can best endure a pimple in the face with confidence."
