It's not so much a book about what happened, he explains, but rather "a book about how it was." It's about "feelings, impressions, experiences and moods."
"Beauty and Horror" is almost the combined war experiences of 20 more or less inconspicuous men and women on both sides of the war, from schoolgirls and botanists to mountaineers, doctors, ambulance drivers and office workers.
Some of these people become heroes.
Some become prisoners of war, lose limbs, go mad or die.
Each of these lives flares up like votive candles in a church, some are added, while others go out.
Englund's book differs from the usual history books.
It also corrects the notion that the First World War was only the devastating war of position on the Western Front.
"Beauty and Terror" wanders with expert view over other war zones: the Alps, the Balkans, the Eastern Front, Mesopotamia, East Africa.
On the soldiers in this book fall beehives, one celebrates Christmas under the pyramids in Egypt, tsetse flies are an insoluble problem.
This is a moving book almost from the beginning.
The war is flooding the lives of these people like a natural disaster, like Hurricane Katrina smelling of cordit.
Imagine you are a woman who is at home with her children and hears cannon fire in the distance. Do you stay or flee?
Who is coming?
Hardly anyone understands what is happening or why this war is being waged at all.
"Missing facts", Englund states, "were furnished with assumptions, assumptions, hopes, fears, fixed ideas, conspiracy theories, dreams, nightmares and rumours."
"Beauty and Terror" follows individuals such as Florence Farmborough, an English nurse in the Russian army, and Richard Stumpf, a young German sailor.
Their stories were mainly taken from memories, letters and other previously published material.
Their life stories can be terrifying or poignant, but they are extremely vivid in Englund ’ s collection of little moments lost in detail.
Many of them act of want and help themselves.
In the story of a German schoolgirl, he tells: "Replacement, everywhere replacement."
"Spare coffee, wrong aluminum, wrong eraser, paper bandages, wooden buttons."
He tells more about the replacement meal in Germany.
He describes "meat made from pressed rice and baked in mutton fat (and last served with a false bone of wood), tobacco made from dried roots and dried potato skins, shoes soled with wood."
There were, as he notes, "837 registered food substitutes that were permitted in the manufacture of sausages, 511 registered coffee substitutes."
Some stories are about honour and bravery.
An American recognizes his own drive for savagery and says of the war: "You feel that this is, in spite of everything, what was intended for men rather than sitting in the armchair, with the evening paper or the bestseller and a cigarette and a whiskey in his hand, and to pretend that such a facade signifies civilization and that there is no barbarism behind one's strengthened and padded shirt chest."
Conversely, a British soldier realizes that he is likely to die and that no one will take notice of it or worry about it.
"When you distance yourself from the idea of sacrificing yourself, you want to think that this happens in front of an audience," he writes.
Instead, it is as terrible as "a condemned man who was secretly hanged."
Other observations deal with old Europe falling apart and new forms of terror.
“The conflict has increasingly become an economic competition, ” writes Englund,“ a war between factories. ”
He captures the arrival of what he calls "a new species in the bestiary of the young century": "the eloquent and ideologically convinced mass murderer in a tailor-made suit who slaughters while sitting behind a desk."
Humans behave in unforeseen ways, and there is frivolous behavior as well as heroism.
Englund discusses the soldiers who actively tried to contract venereal disease from a prostitute in order to escape the front-line service.
"The grotesque expression of this can be found in the trade in gonococcal pus, because soldiers bought and smeared on their genitals in the hope of getting to the hospital," he writes.
"Those who were really desperate rubbed him in the eyes, causing them to be blind the rest of their lives."
In this translation from Swedish by Peter Graves, Englund ’ s poetry becomes supple yet unobtrusive and adapts perfectly to his human task.
In dozens of small scenes, he captures the way the war "unleashed uncontrollable forces in a unique way: extreme nationalism, social revolution, religious hatred."
People are beginning to wonder why their leaders are making them fight.
The best books about the First World War were mostly more falsified like Paul Fuss's "Great War and Modern Memory" or novels like Erich Maria Remarque's "Nothing New in the West" than extensive history books.
Englund ’ s band joins an unconventional hall of fame.
His book has the most devastating ending I have ever read about in a nonfiction book.
I won't give it away anymore.
