Although Breivik may have acted alone, he is far from alone in cyberspace: he spent a lot of time in front of his computer before his attack, chatting with some of the millions of nationalists who support far-right groups on social networks.
After the tragedy this summer, researchers wanted to find out more about these people.
But how to find them?
This is easy - you just have to log in to Facebook.
"We found that it was not difficult to get to them," says Jamie Bartlett, the lead author of a recent report by the British think tank DEMOS on digital populism in Europe.
Facebook ’ s personal data hideout is so encyclopedic, says Bartlett, that researchers simply need to use the site ’ s advertising tool to pinpoint their desired demographic data with scientific accuracy – just as marketers have been doing for years.
Bartlett ’ s team found half a million fans of far-right groups across Europe, and then targeted them with add-ons, but instead of linking to a new band or a new dietary product, the add-ons invited users to a survey that asked about their education, attitudes toward violence, and their own future.
Thanks to Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues were able to interview more than 10,000 supporters of 14 far-right parties in 11 European countries - without ever having to leave their office.
“It ’ s quite a new research method, ” says Bartlett.
Some of the results are hardly surprising. Online supporters of far-right groups are mostly young, male, and angry at immigration.
But in a kind of surprising twist, "those who combine their online activism with an offline activism are more reasonable, more democratic, and less violent than those who remain behind their computer screens."
DEMO ’ s work is just one example of how Facebook is becoming a new hot tool in the hands of scientists.
Idea factories, medical researchers and political scientists use the site to study everything from health issues to social trends such as likes, text messages and status updates.
With more than 800 million active users adding on average three content per day, Facebook's "data supernova" is generating a research boom that has increased the number of scientific works with the name of this page in the title by nearly 800% in the last five years.
For some researchers, the beauty of Facebook is the fact that you can study through this page people who you normally do not reach with your clipboard on the street.
"If you used to try to interview people from the British National Party, it was very difficult to identify them."
“They had to inform the party first and it would never have allowed them to enter, ” Bartlett says.
"On Facebook, all this is gone - you go directly to them."
Others say that the site provides a way to identify and solve social health problems.
A recent study by Dr. Megan Moreno of the University of Wisconsin, Madison, and her colleagues found that students who discussed their intoxication on Facebook are significantly more prone to problem drinking than students who were silent on the subject.
Moreno suggests that equal students, such as residential advisors, monitor the site and help a student if they post too many status updates.
“You can ’ t solve a problem if you haven ’ t recognized it, ” Dimitri Christakis, Morenos Ko ’ author and director of Child Health, Behavior and Development at the Children ’ s Research Institute in Seattle, told the Washington Post.
"We have found a way to identify vulnerable children who otherwise would not have been found."
Facebook also constantly taps into the data of its own population.
