But Facebook users know that the site is watching them, whether they want to or not. In order to play Scrabble with a friend who is thousands of miles away, the site is allowed to expose its own personal data.
But what if Facebook users become part of a survey they don ’ t even know about?
While researchers have strict guidelines on how to collect their data offline, online everything is allowed.
“I don ’ t think many users have even thought about the fact that a researcher could study their profiles, ” says Neil Selwyn, a sociologist at the London Knowledge Lab, about a 2006 study of the public pages of students on Facebook.
"As for her, it was just about her and her friends."
Then there is the question of methodology.
Even offline there is no guarantee that a research participant is absolutely honest.
On Facebook, it is impossible to know how much of the information in a user profile and in posts is true.
“What you say on Facebook and what you do outside of Facebook are two completely different things, ” says Selwyn.
Therefore, despite his years as a technology researcher, Selwyn thinks that a clipboard and a pen are still the best research tools anyone can use.
"There is no substitute for going out into the real world and talking to real people," he says.
"Social research has to deal with the social - and a lot of social life is still going on offline."
