7 lessons from the interview with the late Steve Jobs, which was shown in a theatre this week
After Steve Jobs ’ death on October 5, some compared him to Henry Ford, highlighting engineering genius as a great modern inventor.
But what Apple ’ s fans might find most revealing in the recently rediscovered Jobs ’ interview, which was dusted off this week before special movie screenings in major markets, is how much this creative mind has understood business processes and workflows.
He was certainly a designer, a dreamer, and a self-proclaimed hippie, but he was also a meticulous organizer who diligently crafted diagrams - a man who believed that many managers suffer from "a disease of thought," "that a really great idea accounts for 90 percent of the work... [but] there is an enormous amount of craftsmanship between a great idea and a great product."
In 1995 Bob Cringely developed the TV series "Triumph of the Professional Idiots" about the departure of the personal computer. And he sat together with Jobs for more than an hour, in which they had one of the rare, detailed conversations.
By that time, more than 10 years had passed since jobs had been squeezed out of Apple. And he was already working hard on his new computer company, NeXT, and was looking forward to the widespread adoption of the Internet.
While a small part of Cringley's interview was used in technical idiots, he says that the copy templates of the interview were missing on delivery.
It was only after Jobs ’ death that a complete VHS copy was discovered in the director ’ s garage.
This slightly revised footage forms the basis for the 68-minute film "Steve Jobs: The Lost Interview", which will be coming to the Landmark Theater this Wednesday and Thursday.
For someone known to abhor in-depth interviews, Jobs appears surprisingly eager to explain his technological philosophies and business strategies.
And incredibly thoughtful.
In the course of the interview there are four longer pauses between question and answer - 10 to 15 seconds of reflection, in which Jobs clearly weighs his thoughts and strives for accuracy.
There are also moments when Jobs ’ perfectionism comes to light when he seems impatient with Cringely ’ s questions and pushes him to respond more quickly to issues or subplots of greater importance.
Taken before the era of Pixar, iPod or iPhone, the Lost Interview appears somehow eerily far-sighted when Jobs evaluates what other companies do right or wrong in his opinion and presents his own vision of the future of the computer.
It is one thing to read posthumous appraisals of Jobs' career, but seeing Jobs here as the eager dreamer on the jump to greatness is something very different, original and inspiring.
He has a vision of how things could and should be.
Shortly after he had done all this here, he went off and did it.
A quick look at seven remarkable sequences of the Lost Interview:
How he learned to run a business:
"Throughout the years in business, I always ask," Why are you doing things? "And the answer you always get is," Oh, it's just done like that. "
No one knows why he does what he does. No one in business really thinks about things in detail.
I have noticed that.
Jobs continues his efforts to streamline Apple accounting.
Astonishingly, how costs were recorded - usually starting with "standard costs", which were quantified on the basis of mere assumption and then adjusted with "deviation" - he developed an automated factory that ensured that business costs could be determined down to the smallest detail.
How the Pope was ridiculed:
Jobs talks about the "Blue Box", which he built with Steve Wozniak, a device with which you could sneak into the telephone company and make long-distance calls for free.
Much has been written about the device, but Jobs ’ enthusiasm for describing the Blue Box as an act of self-empowerment is contagious.
He describes how Wozniak and he would test the box by using a paid phone, making a call and then connecting from one AT & T network to another as they loop through as many satellites as possible.
“We sent things around the globe half a dozen times and when you shouted into the phone, it came out in the phone next door a minute later, ” Jobs chuckled.
"We were young and we learned that we could build something ourselves that could control trillions of dollars of infrastructure around the world."
The two of us, we didn ’ t know much, but we could build this little thing that can control a gigantic thing, that was an incredible lesson and I don ’ t think there would be Apple without it.
Jobs continues to talk about a glorious prank that Wozniak and he almost pulled off when they called the Vatican in the middle of the night via Blue Box and wanted to talk to the Pope while imitating Henry Kissinger as best they could.
Since several members of the Catholic hierarchy were summoned in the middle of the night to speak to the American diplomat, the two of them had to laugh before the Pope himself spoke on the phone.
How he fell in love with technology (and called Bill Hewlett unprepared):
At the age of 12, when he was looking for spare parts to build a frequency counter, he looked for Bill Hewlett in the phone book and called him.
Shortly after her 20-minute call, Jobs received a part-time summer job at Hewlett-Packard.
"It had a remarkable impact on me. It was the only company I had seen at that age and it formed my views on what a company was and how well it treated its employees."
Later, Jobs became one of HP ’ s employees who visited the company ’ s research labs in Palo Alto, where he saw “the first desktop computer that was ever produced. ”
He was as big as a suitcase, had a small screen with a brown tube and I fell in love with him.
I would climb up at HP as a teenager and hang on to this machine and write programs for it.
How to improve innovation:
Jobs talks about how to spontaneously invent new products several times in an interview.
Early in his career, when he installed some boards, he was asked by a customer to assemble the whole computer.
He worked with a payment period of only 30 days and had to think through both the assembly and the delivery of the finished equipment.
Later at Apple he remembers the problems he had with the development of a computer mouse:
"I remember striking arguments... They shouted at me that it would take five years [to build a mouse that would cost $300] and I got up, went out and found a manufacturer."
Ninety days later, we had a mouse that we could build for $15. That was incredibly believable.
Over large enterprises, which weaken:
Long before he revived Apple, Jobs foresaw the ways in which so many industrial giants stumbled with their visions and lost control of their shares.
"Let's say you work at IBM or Xerox, so make a better copier or printer, so what?"
They have the share monopoly, so the company is no longer successful.
Sales and marketing make it more successful, so [it ’ s those people] who ultimately run the companies and the product that drives people out of decision making.
The product genius that led to this monopoly position is being eradicated by people who have no concept of good products vs. bad products - craftsmanship necessary.
This happened at Xerox...
Xerox could have owned the entire computer industry.
You could have been ten times bigger, you could have been Microsoft in the 1990s...
They have taken defeat by victory.
About innovation as an art form:
"There is a lot of craftsmanship between a great idea and a great product... when you develop this great idea, it changes and grows."
You learn a lot about your subtleties.
You have to vote, certain things you can't do, but electrons, glass, robots, factories.
You have to remember 5000 things, those concepts, and bring them all together...
In the end it boils down to taste, it boils down to trying to deal with the best stuff that people have created and then trying to bring these things together into what you do.
Picasso said that good artists copy, great artists steal.
We are always shameless in stealing great ideas.
Part of what made Macintosh great was that the people who worked there were musicians, poets, artists, zoologists, historians who happened to be the best computer scientists in the world.
Had it not been for the computer industry, they would have done fantastic things in other areas.
