How to Unmask a Lie
A look at the current headlines shows how worrying and widespread deception and lies are in everyday life.
The Republican presidential candidate, Herman Cain, is busy coping with allegations of sexual harassment by several women, and both sides accuse each other of lying.
Penn State management is accused of perjury for allegedly withholding reports that a retired football coach has sexually abused boys.
Last week, an open microphone was heard when French President Nicolas Sarkozy told US President Barack Obama that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu was a liar.
Lies destroy careers and shake countries.
New York Congressman and Internet exhibitionist Anthony Weidner made a fool of himself by circulating denials that were quickly refuted by incontrovertible evidence.
Former presidential candidate John Edwards is accused of violations of campaign funding, which is related to the cover-up of an extramarital affair.
And then, of course, no one who has experienced it forgets the media circus that President Bill Clinton triggered when he lied during his second term in the Oval Office about his sexual relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
Stories of cheating in school and at college are widespread.
There have been incidents in which teachers have given their students the answers to the exam so that they are good at their own performance checks.
Mentors, who should teach the opposite, send a message that lying and cheating are okay.
How much deception do we experience?
Studies show that we lie between 10 and 200 times a day.
But many of these lies are considered white lies.
Another study shows that strangers lie to each other three times during the first 10 minutes of a meeting.
Recognizing and "uncovering lies" is one that is important for everyone to learn, both for personal and professional reasons.
Far from a parlor game, such as charades, in which the goal is to shout "Have you!", the unmasking of deception is a serious area of knowledge based on scientific data collected over the past six decades at prestigious universities conducting wide-ranging research projects, particularly in the fields of psychology and physiology.
One result of the research is that most of the old myths about lying have been unmasked.
Lies look you in the eyes.
They do not always stutter, stammer, blush and fidget.
This does not mean, however, that these liars are difficult to uncover and expose.
An experienced liar can penetrate the truth by learning about the structure of the claim, the fine facial expressions, the question and timing.
I have spent several years studying the scientific results of the vast and ever-growing area of uncovering, and it is clear that uncovering a deception is a modern skill that is easy to learn and helps us to navigate in our complex world, especially when hiring or questioning people or negotiating or administering is one of your professional responsibilities.
Good liars are very good at judging other people, arousing their interest and controlling their own emotions, and they intuitively sense how they are perceived by others.
Thanks to research, we know that extrovert people are more likely than introvert people to lie, that men are more likely to come up with "self-centered" lies than women, whose lies are more "oriented to others" - usually to protect the feelings of others - that married people are less likely to lie to their partners than unmarried people (but the lies they tell are mostly "bolder lies").
We also know that when a person is exposed as an evildoer, others feel less guilty for lying to that person.
How do you know if someone is lying?
First, observe the normal behavior of that person.
This is called "baselining", the starting position.
It provides a reference point for the later evaluation of changes.
Observe the attitude, the laughter, the voice quality of your subject.
They should know better when someone normally trips his foot all the time, so they don ’ t accuse him wrongly if he trips his foot during a meeting.
Then watch out for accumulations of conspicuous verbal and non-verbal behaviour.
Consider these accumulations as alarm bells that ring, not as evidence of an uncovering.
People who deceive may freeze when they try to remember their story. Perhaps, their feet point toward the door or they lean toward the exit, changing their position in a significant way, or showing a "relaxation after the recruitment interview," this deep, relaxing exhalation and the change in posture when all the hard questions are over.
Questioners often erroneously signal that a job interview is over, only to look for this relaxation after the job interview.
Also pay attention to the language of your subject.
The slip of Scott Peterson is famous when he used the past tense, when he claimed that his dead wife was still alive and triggered a national search for her.
Deceiving persons can also use a distancing language: "I had no sexual relationship with this woman... Miss Lewinsky" or if one repeats a tricky question on the whole.
The most common verbal signs are subtle.
Some people use "qualifying language" when they answer a tricky question: "Well... to tell you the truth... as far as I know... to the best of my knowledge and conscience."
This makes the answer more perceptive than objective, often causing alarm bells to ring.
There is no magic cure for uncovering lies, but you can learn abilities that allow you to uncover them.
Thanks to these skills, everyone is less likely to fall victim to fraud, both in their private and professional lives.
