Climatic adversity slowed down the economy
In the first year of Mario López Valdez ’ s government, Sinaloa saw a rise in unemployment and undeclared work, while foreign investment declined and the economy stagnated.
2011 will be remembered in the economic history of Sinaloa. It is the first year that Mario López Valdez, who describes himself as the initiator of change and raised great hopes for economic growth, is in government. However, as a result of climatic adversities, there can be no talk of growth; on the contrary, the main economic indicators have deteriorated.
The low temperatures in February not only caused losses amounting to millions in agriculture, but also put tight limits on the growth of the state economy and caused a general decline in economic activity of 3.6 percent in the first quarter of the year. This is mainly due to the historical reduction of agricultural development by 31.16 percent, which slowed down other economic sectors.
According to a report on the effects of frost published by the Consejo Mexicano para el Desarrollo Rural Sustentable (Mexican Council for Sustainable Agricultural Development), 582,000 hectares of agricultural land were damaged, of which 78.03 percent were completely destroyed and the remaining 21.07 percent were partially destroyed. Vegetable, maize and chickpea cultivation were particularly affected.
The decline in economic activity until November has led to a continuous increase in unemployment in the Mexican State. Instituto Nacional de Estadística y Geografía observed a rapid increase in unemployment during the first quarter of the year, with 55.053 Sinaloans without employment, or 4.53% of the working population, from January to March. Unemployment rose to 5.28% in the second quarter and to 6.19% from July to September, resulting in 74,000 unemployed in Sinaloa, which is 18,969 more than in the first quarter.
Less liquidity
Unemployment in Sinaloa in the year is due to several factors. The economist Gerardo López Cervantes, Dean of the Faculty of Economics and Social Sciences of the University of Autónoma (UAS), comments that the policies of public institutions indirectly explain the growing unemployment.
"What we are currently seeing is an increase in unemployment, which has to do with several factors, including the loss of liquidity in the market as a result of the cuts in funding introduced by the legislation passed by Congress to combat money laundering, because for those who illegally pile up dollars, it is not easy to make them work for themselves, invest them or use them for anything else," he said.
Stopping migration
López Cervantes pointed out that there is also a demographic factor inherent in growing unemployment.
"The number of people leaving the country looking for work abroad, particularly in the United States, has decreased, partly because of the entry problems and partly because it is difficult to find work there as well," he says. "These people stay here and look for work, which increases unemployment."
Undeclared work
The analysis of the labour market in Sinaloa is even more serious if one takes into account the high proportion of undeclared work, which, according to INEGI, comprises 60.38% of the country ’ s employees who work without contributing to the social security system.
Unemployment and undeclared work are supplemented by low wages, the lowest in all of Mexico, according to the statistics of the Instituto Mexicano del Seguro Social (Mexican Social Security Institute) and the Secretaría del Trabajo y Previsión Social (Mexican Department of Labor and Social Welfare).
The average monthly income of workers in Sinaloa until September was 5,352 pesos, much lower than the national average of 7,375 pesos.
Decline in FDI
In addition to the reduction in economic activity and growing unemployment, 2011 saw the biggest decline in foreign direct investment (FDI) in the last ten years. According to the Secretaría de Economía (State Economic Authority), the FDI from January to June was $630 597, a decrease of 87.74% compared to $5,143,312 in the same period last year.
The Secretaría de Desarrollo Económico del Gobierno (Government Office for Economic Development), for its part, recorded a total investment of 17,280,000 pesos in 2011, mainly from companies in the tertiary sector.
The Debt
In the face of the economic crisis, the state government applied to the national congress in July for a loan of 3,000,000,000 pesos to be invested in infrastructure projects in the 18 municipalities in order to reactivate the economy.
Reactions
For the representatives of the business community, the first year of the government made Mario López Valdés incapacitated.
Miguel Loredo López, president of the Cámara Nacional de la Industria de la Transformación (Mexican State Chamber of Manufacturing Industry), argued that in 2011 no efforts were made to harmonize the views of the different sectors, including the state government.
"Economic activity in Sinaloa has been very poor this year, hard work is needed to regain the ground lost this year, and we have to work twice in 2012. Everyone's efforts, and in particular the progress of the already well-coordinated government team, have not been sufficiently coordinated," he said.
Slow economic development
Loredo López said that events such as the frost at the beginning of the year made the economic development of the country more difficult and slowed down.
“The low economic flow is the result of several events, including the frost. One of the most important impacts is a slowing economy that is not moving enough to create an economic dynamic that could create an acceptable flow of processes, products and services, so we will close the year well below our expectations, ” he said.
Redefining vocation
Teodoro Salazar Uriarte, president of the Confederación Patronal de la República Mexicana (Confederation of Mexican Entrepreneurs) in Sinaloa, said the state must be encouraged to engage in more dynamic productive activities.
"In general, we have observed that work has been done. We believe that it is necessary to develop a long-term program to redefine the economic vocation and line of the country, because it is important to activate all material and human resources of Sinaloa," he said.
There is a lot to do
The President of Coparmex stressed the importance of developing a future perspective that will steer the government ’ s efforts in a better direction.
"In general, I would say that the government has achieved good results in several areas. Economic development has progressed, but it is important to develop a long-term program," he explained.
He stressed that the current state power had made progress with the government.
"There are areas where it can be said that the government has acted more comprehensively," he said. "What I can say is that work has been done and that the government is aware that there is still a lot of work to be done."
