The court approved for 2015 the transition to digital television in Mexico
The changeover from analogue to digital signals has been one of the most important changes worldwide in recent years.
The Supreme Court of Mexico (SCJN) rejected the constitutional complaints filed by the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies against the presidential decree, which requires the switchover from analog to digital signals to be brought forward from 2021 to 2015, owing to the lack of eight votes required to challenge the law.
A minority of four ministers, including the President of the Supreme Court, Juan Silva Meza, believed that President Felipe Calderón had not exceeded his jurisdiction when he issued the decree with the details of the switchover to digital terrestrial television.
By that decision, the constitutional dispute initiated by the Senate was rejected on the ground that it did not obtain the qualified majority of eight votes required for the Court to rule on the issue of constitutionality or non-constitutionality. Thus, the law remains in force.
In the project for the lawsuit, drafted by Minister Olga Sánchez Cordero, it was proposed that the Legislative Decree be declared unconstitutional, since the Federal Commission for Telecommunications (Cofetel) is responsible for the regulation of radio and television, and therefore the Legislative Decree would be contrary to hierarchical principles and legislative reservations.
Only Zaldívar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and Sánchez Cordero voted in favour of the project.
With this argument, both the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies filed constitutional complaints against the Decree-Law. Once the complaints were accepted, Minister Sánchez Cordero no longer applied the Decree-Law and ceased all activities related to the establishment of digital transmission.
The Council of Ministers also rejected the complaint submitted by the Chamber of Deputies without entering into the debate on the project, which was also the responsibility of Minister Sánchez Cordero.
In his speech, the Prime Minister said that he did not agree with the arguments of the project, in the sense that the regional government should not regulate the measures that the public administration should take with general regulations.
"I do not believe that doing so would compromise the independence of the regulator," she said. "It is the central government that is responsible for the planning of strategic policy areas, such as the telecommunications sector, for constitutional reasons, because it manages state affairs.
The replacement of analogue signals by digital is one of the most important changes that has taken place in recent years around the world, and it causes better use of the radioelectric spectrum, increased signal quality and more channels.
The postponement of the changeover, she said, was a postponement of the benefits of digitisation, which was a decision in the public interest that was not purely technical, "because it included economic, social, political and security aspects."
These matters, she stressed, "necessitated the action of the entire system; according to the principle of economic government by the state, they included a set of characteristics that the constitution placed in the hands of the central government."
She recalled that many countries around the world have already made the digital transition, through government, despite having highly specialized facilities.
It could not be concluded that by issuing the contested decree, the government encroached on the powers of the Congress, because the laws passed by the legislature would be respected, ” she assured.
The possibility to count the ballots in Michoacán individually is being considered
According to the data of PREP, the difference between the first and the second place in the election of the governor is almost 27 percent, with 879 votes out of a total of 6074 not yet counted.
The possibility of counting the ballots individually is a reality in the Michoacán elections this year, because according to the data provided by the Preliminaries Electoral Program (PREP), the difference between first and second place in the gubernatorial elections is almost 27 percent, with 879 votes out of a total of 6074 not yet counted.
In this regard, the President of the Consejo General del Instituto Electoral de Michoacán (IEM), María de los Ángeles Llanderal Zaragoza, recalled that just last November 9, the electoral body had adopted a series of regulations aimed at harmonizing local regulations with the electoral reforms of the states.
It is worth remembering that Michoacán had not adapted his political constitution, electoral law, or law on electoral justice to the reforms approved by Congress, so that they did not enter into force in this round. Governor Leonel Godoy Rangel avoided their publication in the Official Gazette within the stipulated deadlines, arguing or objecting to them.
On 9 November, the Supreme Court of Justice of the Nation (SCJN) ruled on the constitutional complaint lodged by the local legislature, declaring the voice of the State Representative on constitutional reforms "invalid and unlawful," since he does not have the right to "decide or veto."
María de los Ángeles Llanderal said in an interview about the possibility of counting the votes individually that thanks to the adoption of the guidelines by the Consejo General del IEM, there is now the possibility that the local electoral authority can count the ballots partially or completely.
Thus, under the following conditions, the votes contained in one or more ballot packages may be partially counted The results in the minutes do not agree; the minutes of the counting and calculation of votes are not on file or are not in the possession of the chairman of the election committee or there are obvious errors or amendments in the minutes.
Furthermore, the total count of the completed ballot papers can take place if there is a difference between the presumed winner and the runner-up, which is equal to or less than one percent, provided that at the beginning of the meeting there is an explicit request from the party or coalition chairman, who is the second of the above-mentioned candidates.
The counting of votes may also take place in its entirety if it is established after the end of the ordinary calculation that the difference between the presumed winner and the runner-up is equal to or less than one percent, provided that there is an explicit request from a representative of the party whose candidate has finished second. In this case, the ballot packages that were subject to a partial counting would be excluded.
It is worth noting that the elections in Morelia are in the same situation where, according to the PREP, the difference between first and second place is almost 0.16%, although the votes of 129 out of a total of 923 election minutes have not yet been counted.
