On Wednesday formation of the new Italian government
The Prime Minister designate, Mario Monti, will meet tomorrow with the President of Italy to present the new government to face the crisis that has brought Italy to the brink of economic collapse.
The Prime Minister designate, Mario Monti, will meet tomorrow with the President of Italy to present the new government to face the crisis that has brought Italy to the brink of economic collapse.
A note from the presidential palace announced that the Monti, who was appointed on Sunday, would meet on Wednesday with the President of the Republic, Giorgio Napolitano, to confirm the formation of the government.
He is expected to present a cabinet composed mostly of technocrats, though it is not yet clear when the new prime minister will take office.
Monti said he would present to the President the results of the talks with the political parties to form a government.
"I want to reaffirm my absolute confidence in our country's ability to cope with these difficult times," the former EU Commissioner told journalists.
Monti did not explicitly confirm the formation of the government, but his comments show that the obstacles have been overcome.
"The framework is now well defined," he added.
In less than three days, Monti managed to form a government, which is much less time than usual. Meanwhile, Italy is struggling against a political and financial crisis that has driven the cost of debt to an intolerable level.
The new government, led by former EU Commissioner Monti, must adopt a tough austerity package demanded by the eurozone ’ s leaders in order to regain diminished confidence in Italy.
The pressure of haste on Monti was exacerbated by the volatility of the market, as a result of which Italian government bonds were priced at 7% for 10 years, the level at which Greece and Ireland were forced to apply for the European bailout.
Emma Marcegaglia, president of the Italian industry association Confindustria, told the press after a meeting with Monti: "We said we would do everything possible to support this government."
We believe that this government is the last chance for Italy to emerge from this emergency.
Monti's chances of success were considerably increased by the support of Silvio Berlusconi's PDL party, which had to resign on Saturday as a result of the crisis.
"We believe that the efforts of Professor Monti are destined to produce good results," said Angelino Alfano, Secretary of the Center Right Party.
Support for the PDL, the largest party in Italy, is essential because, until now, many of its members have spoken out against the majority technocratic government that Monti is forming.
Support from Parliament
Monti ’ s new government needs strong parliamentary support to implement what are probably unpopular austerity measures.
Resisting his efforts or delaying reforms could once again lead to a devastating attack on the financial markets.
The Italian Association of Foreign Banks is also exerting pressure, pointing out that Monti's failure is a disaster.
Monti started his debates on Monday with political parties, trade unions and business associations, as well as youth and women's organisations.
The session is due to be concluded on Tuesday evening.
Monti was appointed this Sunday by Napolitano, who has set in motion an extremely rapid change of government in response to the crisis.
After a brief sigh of relief at the end of last week, when it became known that Berlusconi would resign, the uncertainty about the new prime minister ’ s success has brought the cost of Italian government bonds back to critical limits.
Saving Italy with a national debt of €1.8 trillion would be too much for the current EU bailout.
Monti said that his government must last until the next elections, which are expected to be held in 2013, despite predictions that politicians will only give him time to implement the reforms, rather than bringing the elections forward.
Monti said he would like to include politicians in his cabinet, but the major parties insist that it should consist only of technicians, an indication of their concerns about the procedure imposed by financial market pressure.
Political sources indicate that mutual distrust and disagreements between the parties complicate the involvement of political figures.
