You never repeat your repertoire.
Why?
I think that ’ s partly because we have nine records and we can play over 120 songs. Everyone likes a different song, so it ’ s not easy to decide which one to play.
If we include two or three songs that we haven ’ t played for a long time into our repertoire, we can keep up our concentration better and they surprise us because they remind us of the reasons why we liked these songs. Otherwise, they might fall into oblivion.
That makes the show more interesting for us and I think that ’ s why it ’ s interesting for the audience.
With this tour you celebrate your twenty years of history.
When you look back, do you find it hard to believe in your success?
Yes, totally.
First of all, I think that none of us imagined playing in a great rock band for more than 20 years, and it seems like a dream.
We continue to count on this blessing and find it great to be able to make music together even now.
We like each other and are enthusiastic about making music.
We are lucky to be able to travel to the places in the world that we have always wanted to visit.
Things could not be better.
What did it mean for you to have actively participated in the birth of the grunge?
It has always been an honor to belong to this group of big bands.
We are good friends with the people from Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains.
It is surprising and abundantly unusual when a movement emerges from a group of friends.
Every now and then a band emerges from a city, but it is unusual when five or ten groups come out of the same city at the same time.
We are proud and honored to be a part of the Seattle-like group.
Sometimes we still play together.
Last year we were at a festival with Alice in Chains and in Canada with Mudhoney and we saw Soundgarden on tour. We are still happy to be friends with them all and it honors us to be part of this emerging Seattle sound.
It is also very unusual that a band like yours has stayed together with the same musicians for such a long time.
Yes, four of us have been playing together for 21 years and Matt (Cameron) joined us 13 years ago, which alone is much more time than many bands last.
First of all, I believe that we are all happy to be alive, and we also care about each other.
We are all close friends, which is why musical paths have opened up, giving each individual the freedom to experiment.
One trusts the other and his music. We couldn ’ t do better.
Your relationship with fame has not always been easy. On the other hand, thanks to your success, you have always been able to do what you wanted.
How do you find a balance?
The way we have grown has made it easier for us to find a balance.
We make sure not to tour too often, because it is too easy to fall in love with this game with huge crowds who love your music.
As long as you think that people have come because of the music, it reminds you that you have to pay attention to the music and what it has brought to life, without being obsessed with being a famous rock star. We ’ ve never been interested in that anyway.
What memories do you have of your other project Mother Love Bone?
I think we wrote very good songs and in the beginning it was great.
For three years we were a band that had never released a record until the death of Andy (Andrew Woods).
We were disappointed to have taken so long. We are still good friends with Bruce (Fairweather) and Greg (Gilmore), who built up the band with us. When I hear a song or see photos, I think about what an incredible person Andy was and how he made me laugh. It was always a pleasure to go to work, to laugh together and to talk about music and football and many other topics.
He was an extraordinary person and we miss him.
The domestic band Las Robertas are responsible for the opening of the show in Costa Rica.
Is it true that you know their work, especially Eddie Vedder, and have therefore chosen the band for the opening?
Yes, the production sent us videos from several groups and we liked this band best. So we are curious to see what Las Robertas can offer live. It ’ s going to be exciting.
Why do you change the lyrics of Yellow Ledbetter every time you play live?
This is a question for Ed (Eddie Vedder), I have no idea.
He sings it, and I think he sings the first thing that comes to his mind.
Who influenced you as a bass player?
From so many +
Among the first to come to mind are Geezer Butler, John Entwistle, C. J. Ramone, John Doe, Paul McCartney, Chuck Dukowski...
There are so many that I could talk all afternoon about the bassists I like.
How did Pearl Jam manage to keep the grunge alive even though it is no longer a fad?
I think we all do not feel very attached to the word grunge.
When I think about it, I think of the bands I mentioned earlier, like Mudhoney, Soundgarden, Nirvana and all the others that came up at the same time. If they are still important today, I think it ’ s great, because it ’ s worth listening to this music and bands like Mudhoney are now making better music than ever before.
Initially her music was darker, now it is more positive.
Why?
This is interesting, because I think there are some songs on the new album that could seem a bit frivolous, but there are also other songs like The End or Just Breathe that are classified as very dark songs, although they also have something positive about them.
Both of them brought tears to my eyes when I heard Ed play them. They ’ re very dark songs.
I think when you get older and something traumatic has happened in your life - e.g. when you lose a family member or a friend - it influences your artistic work and your music and these two songs embody that for me.
But I am also of the opinion that you can be a happy person and still make dark music.
