Fujimori hospitalized again for medical examinations
Former President Alberto Fujimori was admitted to a public hospital on Tuesday to examine the muscle loss of his legs, his family doctor informed.
72-year-old Fujimori, who is serving 25 years in prison for human rights violations during his reign (1990 - 2000), has several illnesses, including tongue cancer, which has been operated on four times and is under control.
Alejandro Aguinaga, member of Congress and his personal doctor, told the television that Fujimori was being examined for three days at the Peruvian National Institute of Neoplasic Enfermedades to determine the cause of his pain and muscle loss in the lower limbs.
Aguinaga commented that in his opinion Fujimori could be pardoned for humanitarian reasons. Nevertheless, he did not want this because he considered him innocent.
He has been operated on four times for tongue cancer and has lost 18 kilos in weight. Additionally, the doctor listed other illnesses such as severe erosive gastritis, a cyst in the pancreas, kidney stones, high blood pressure and circulation problems in the legs.
Fujimori has been held in the National Directorate of Specialist Operations of the Police since September 2007.
In April 2009, he was sentenced to 25 years in prison for the murder of 25 people by the death squad of the Peruvian army, which was secretly active during his reign.
Mujica travels to Mexico to strengthen political relations
An official delegation, led by Uruguayan President José Mujica and composed of several ministers and entrepreneurs, will start their visit to Mexico on Tuesday to expand trade between the two countries and discuss political issues in the region.
Mujica will meet next Wednesday with his Mexican counterpart Felipe Calderón. According to the Uruguayan president, this will be the culmination of his busy schedule with politicians, business people and a meeting with the Uruguayan collective living in Mexico.
The meeting of both presidents in the city of Guadalajara "is suitable for the exchange of information on all policy areas between the two countries", announced the Presidency of the South American country on its website.
According to local media, Mujica is seeking Calderón ’ s support for the incident with France when French leader Nicolas Sarkozy put the South American country on a list of tax havens at the G-20 summit in the French city of Cannes.
In his discourse, Sarkozy threatened to exclude from the international community those countries that still operate as tax havens, a declaration that Uruguay rejected, prompting a request to its ambassador in the European country.
Mexico has been chairing the G20 since November, a group of the most powerful emerging and industrialized countries in the world. An agreement on the exchange of tax information to avoid double taxation with the South American country has been in place since January this year.
In recent years, the Uruguayan government has tried to speed up the implementation of tax information exchange agreements in order to be removed from the Organisation for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD) 'grey list' of countries that have not adopted all the international standards for tax cooperation.
On the business side, a Free Trade Agreement between Mexico and Uruguay has been in place since 2004 and has contributed to a growing exchange of goods between the two countries.
The moustachioed installer enters the third dimension with "Super Mario 3D Land"
Super Mario has fought tirelessly for 25 years for the rescue of Princess Peach from the clutches of the evil Bowser, but until now never in three dimensions: in "Super Mario 3D Land" he fights for the love of the girl in stereo and technology.
The game, which will be released this month on the world ’ s store counters, has been tailored from the outset to the characteristics of the Nintende 3DS portable console, which can be used to play three-dimensionally without special glasses.
"Mario is the character who has to say how stereoscopy works without glasses," affirmed Omar Álvarez, who is in charge of the Spanish Nintendo press at the launch of the video game in Madrid.
Álvarez explained that "Super Mario 3D Land" was "the first video game from Nintendo that was developed from the beginning for this console", because until now successful articles like "Star Fox 64 3D" or "Zelda: Ocarine of time 3D" were adaptations of existing titles.
The speaker of Nintendo underlined that although it is three-dimensional, "Super Mario 3D Land" is an "affordable" video game that allows a fast, fluid game.
Álvarez confirmed that "Super Mario 3D Land" contains two games in one: The first part is "light" to capture the less sophisticated users.
After that, the experts can "turn a second round" through the different game levels, which are becoming more and more difficult.
In addition, users can choose in real time between an "aggressive D" or one that only affects the depth of the action. To overcome the obstacles without becoming a victim of the "optical effects", however, must always be played three-dimensionally.
This excursion of Super Mario into the three-dimensional world also means the figure ’ s return to a portable console, which has not been the case since 2005.
With this video game Nintendo winks at the fans of the saga and repeats the recipe for success of the latest editions: The mustache installer has to overcome platforms full of dangers in order to free the princess Peach.
However, the player comes across news about the movements, the environment, the disguises and the enemies - and a "playable" Luigi.
Colom guarantees delivery of Portillo to the United States
The President of Guatemala, Álvaro Colom, announced this Tuesday that he would allow the extradition of former Governor Alfonso Portillo to be held responsible in the United States for the $70 million money laundering conspiracy.
That is the end of the process on the US request for the extradition of Portillo, so that he can be tried there.
In a press conference, Colom confirmed that his decision was based on the independence of the judiciary and the government, taking into account that a court had already ordered the extradition.
He stressed that he had not interfered in court decisions during his government and had granted all extradition requests he was informed of.
In addition to Portillo, Sergio Ruano Marroquín, Edgar Estrada Morales and Víctor Estrada Paredes, both of whom were extradited for drug trafficking, were extradited for murder and aggravated injury.
The procedure of Colom is a government act, which takes place, if all judicial and constitutional instances for the conviction of the former Staaat president (2000 - 2004) are exhausted.
In accordance with the decisions of the Fifth Criminal Court and the Constitutional Court of Guatemala, Portillo must be extradited if his legal situation in Guatemale is clarified and his human rights are guaranteed.
Portillo was acquitted of the embezzlement of 120 million Quetzales in the Ministry of Defense during his term of office. This trial preceded the extradition, but the minister objected and reopened the case.
Trinijove has helped 6,000 young people threatened with social exclusion
The organisation was set up to prevent the marginalisation of young people without vocational training.
The first 25 years of life of the social welfare organisation Trinijove have led to important results: in this quarter of a century 6000 young people threatened with social exclusion have been supported to find a way out of their difficult situation.
In addition, there are over 100 jobs created for this social group.
Yesterday, the anniversary was marked by an event in the former factory buildings of Fabra i Coats, in which over 300 people took part.
Trinijove was founded in 1986 in the district of Trinitat Vella with the aim of helping young people with a low level of education, without work, with drug problems that were threatened by the risk of marginality.
Yesterday ’ s celebration in Sant Andreu was attended by a large number of persons in charge of the institutions that have worked with the association over the past 25 years.
The participation of political representatives of different tendencies during the election campaign demonstrated the impartiality of the work carried out by Trinijove.
In addition to the President of the Generalitat (Parliament of the Autonomous Region of Catalonia), Artur Mas, and his predecessor Jordi Pujol, the former Socialist Education Minister Ernest Maragall and the former Mayor and currently on the left Green Councillor Ricard Goma took part in the celebrations.
The large hall of Fabra i Coats was also visited by the current Catalan Minister for Social Affairs and the Family, Josep Lluís Cleries, and the Director General of the Social Services of La Caixa Savings Bank, Jaume Lanaspa.
Mas stressed that Trinijove was born in very difficult times and that today's times are no less complicated, but added that the work done so far is "a good basis".
For the President of the Generalitat, Trinijove is an example that knows how to fight against difficult circumstances and gives hope to people in difficulty.
"The economic crisis is nothing new for the club and the work it is doing," he explained.
Occupied house, where huge parties were held, was evicted
The owners occupied 11 of the 13 apartments in the building at 51 Balmes Street (Barcelona).
The twelve squatters left the building yesterday afternoon without resistance.
Everything indicates that the nightmares of the neighbours of house no. 51 on the street Balmes have come to an end.
Twelve people voluntarily left the building they had illegally occupied yesterday at noon, where they had organised huge festivals which had driven the neighbourhood to despair, and the eviction was carried out by order of the courts without police intervention.
After the eviction, the lock was replaced to avoid a similar situation.
"From now on, access will be controlled," confirmed the property manager.
The squatters, who occupied 11 of the 13 apartments in the building - the others were inhabited - took the entire electrical system and part of the water supply, painted the walls and left behind all kinds of garbage, especially cans of alcoholic beverages.
Huge parties were held on the three lower floors, lasting up to two days and driving the tenants to despair.
Next to the building is a discotheque, Balmes 51, which also suffered damage.
Her owner, Maria Pantinat, told Europa Press that her business had fallen by 80% since the squatting began.
The owner of the discotheque pointed out that the squatters were competing unfairly because they sold the drinks for three euros, while they cost 10 euros at the discotheque.
In addition, the owner of the leisure centre had been denounced by the neighbours for disturbing the peace, while according to her, the noise did not come from the visitors of the disco, but from the squatters, and in particular from the guests of the festivities that were organised there, and which, according to the angry neighbours, have been growing more and more in recent weeks.
The person in charge of the nightclub said that the harassment was so great that she agreed with the owner of the building not to have to pay rent for the last nine months.
The Guardia Urbana (Municipal Police) also confirmed that they have received more complaints from their neighbours in recent weeks.
Last week, Alberto Fernández Díaz, the leader of the PP (Popular Party) in Barcelona City Council, called for the immediate removal of the building and for the problems of civil coexistence and the downfall of the neighbourhood to be tackled.
He explained that before the summer, only one floor of the building had been occupied, but that the squatters had penetrated all the floors of the building and almost all the apartments in recent months. In some cases, there had even been thefts.
In this sense, he added that "it is necessary to put an end to impunity and to clamp down on the anti-social actions in the building."
