Park or mountain?
Apart from the arguments about fees, the architects agree to the invitation to tender.
The urban call for tenders for the 16 gates reopens the debate on the importance of Collserola in Barcelona.
In the mid-1980s, at the height of the disappearance of the Corporación Metropolitana de Barcelona (CMB), this administration published its libellous pamphlet on the promotion of Collserola.
The brochure described the mountain as a huge park in Barcelona city.
It was even compared in figures with New York ’ s Central Park.
With the sinking of the CMB in 1987, the park became in the eyes of many again the upper limit of Barcelona, because the capital of Catalonia is one of the few that does not spread in a north-south direction, but upwards (mountains) and downwards (sea).
The classification of Collserola as a natural park plays with this idea.
The model was no longer Central Park, but Yellowstone with wild boars in the role of the yogi bear.
This was the case when, in September, the city issued a huge invitation to tender, consisting of 16 competitions, for further access gates to Collserola.
There is no doubt that a gate refers to the concept of a park.
Either that is the case, or someone intends to set gates on the countryside.
The question arises: Collserola, Park or Mountain?
The call for proposals is the talk of all Barcelona architects, not only from an organisational point of view, but also with a view to reflecting on the city.
It is almost a recurrent theme to which two members of this old-established caste, who meet in the elevator, can fall back.
And it is precisely this fact that provides the material for one of the rare similarities between what three Barcelona architects think and some university professors who applied for the project.
Miguel Roldán, Daniel Modol and Marta Bayona: The tender is appropriate.
For Roldán, after the attack on the coast, "it is necessary" to speak about the "front on the mountains", as far as the discourse of Ildefons Cerda, about the green apples, has not been carried out.
"One should start from the principle that Barcelona's largest park is the beach.
Among other things, because it is easily accessible.
Collserola is more complex, "says the architect, for whom the title" Gates of Collserola "contains a" lexical trap ": one should not imagine it" as access to a park, but as a delimitation of areas in which one must act. "
Modol, like Roldán and Bayona with urban experience, regards the proposal as an "intellectual challenge" that involves "some dangers".
Dangers arising from the "uncertainty that shaping a public space entails today" after the experiences of the 1980s, which had their "swan song" in the forum area.
The first fear is to limit oneself to what may be built on.
"Confining something always means determining the next step", i.e. exceeding it.
"We have to think about new urban planning tools, because the current ones [referring to the Plan General Metropolitano (PGM)] can lead to a real catastrophe."
Modol, who adheres more closely to the question, simply says that the side of Collserola that goes towards Vallesana "can be understood as a park that does not go towards Barcelona", for purely topographical reasons.
Modol points out that there is already a study by the Patronage of Collserola, which "should not fall on deaf ears", although he is grateful to the municipality for giving his committee the opportunity to participate in this project "from the first moment".
Furthermore, he notes that the proximity of the mountain to the city is the leaflet that enables architects to participate in the debate, although he expresses his "doubts" as to whether this technical profile should guide the multidisciplinary teams that have been created ("just the right thing," he says). "We architects should only be a tool."
Bayona suggests that the answer to the question in the title of this article is complex, because there is no global view of Collserola in the tender conditions: "There were 16 competitions in cross-section," he says, "on the mountain axis of the sea. But there is no longitudinal perspective that considers the area in its entirety."
At least in his case, this has led to him taking part in the 16 competitions.
Otherwise, the program and the definition of a project for a gate would collide with that of the architect of the gate next to it.
In his opinion, the city should absolutely guarantee that the strip directly above the Ronda de Dalt is equipped in its entire length in such a way that a smooth transition between the city and green areas is created.
Casino awards Jonás Larrazábal who comes free
After 72 days of silence, the commissioner of the Casino Red freed the brother of the mayor of Monterrey from the trial against him for alleged extortion.
After 72 days of imprisonment, Manuel Jonás Larrazábal is released after being forgiven by the commissioner of Casino Red in the second criminal court of the district, which is conducting the case against the brother of the mayor of Monterrey for extortion.
After the assassination attempt on the Casino Royale, Sergio Gil García, the owner of Casino Red, published a series of photos and videos showing Manuel Jonás, who presumably forces him to pay a sum of money in order for the city administration to authorize the secret operation of the betting house.
