Secretary Dionisio Pérez Jácome gives details of the plane crash that claimed the lives of Secretary of Government Francisco Blake and seven others.
The Secretaría de Comunicaciones y Transportes - SCT (Secretariat for Communications and Transport in Mexico) informed that the results of the investigation into the accident, in which the Secretary of the Government Francisco Blake Mora and seven other persons were killed, indicate that the helicopter, with all its intact structure, crashed directly against the ground without the pilot being able to make an emergency landing.
At a press conference Dionisio Pérez Jácome, Secretary of Communications and Transport, mentioned that the pilot had confirmed before take-off that the weather conditions were suitable for the flight.
"The fact that the propeller blades were in contact with trees at a height of 25 metres, with the helicopter losing its fuselage, seems to indicate that the helicopter had had several ground contacts."
He also explained that the helicopter was built for 19 passengers, which is why it fulfilled all the conditions for transporting personnel.
In addition, he said that no helicopter parts were found during the investigations in the area where the machine had run down.
"During the search, no aircraft parts were found in other places, the impact affected the entire structure.
The helicopter was built for 19 passengers, which is why it fulfilled all requirements for passenger transport.
The area has an inclination of 7 to 30 degrees.
The priority at the moment is to get the results of the investigation as soon as possible, but it could take several months, perhaps even a year.
For his part, Gilberto López Meyer, General Director of Aeropuertos y Servicios Auxiliares (Secretariat for Aircraft and Auxiliary Services in Mexico), assured that the helicopter of the Estado Mayor Presidencial had flown at cruising speed at the impact and that the plane had fallen on a soft slope.
"This information reinforces the assumption that it was a normal flight operation at the time of impact."
At a press conference, SCT head Pérez Jácome enumerated six relevant points that should be taken into account in the investigation:
Visual flight:
In accordance with the flight standards, it was a flight according to the rules of visual flight. This means that the crew must have had sufficient visibility during the flight and on the ground.
Weather conditions:
The AICM recorded suitable weather conditions at take-off. During the onward flight to the border area between Mexico City and Mexico City, some low-hanging clouds appeared.
Selected flight routes:
It is possible that the team had chosen a lower area with better visibility towards the Cuernavaca Valley due to the clouds.
Impact site:
The impact coordinates and the last radar recording of the helicopter coincide. Possibly there was neither a loss of control over the airplane nor a deviation from the flight route before the impact.
Dispersion of the remains of the aircraft in a limited area:
The information available so far indicates that the helicopter had crashed from the straight and lateral directions.
The pattern of the scattered aircraft remains suggests that the helicopter with its intact structure had crashed onto the ground.
No evidence of fire or explosion:
The remains of the aircraft at the scene of the accident indicate neither fire nor explosion.
The latest results indicate several soil contacts.
During the on-site investigations, aircraft parts were found at an altitude of 9,200 feet above sea level, and the terrain is steep with a slope of between seven and thirty degrees.
The photos show the sequence in which the helicopter probably broke.
Some information indicates that the helicopter may have had several ground contacts.
After a meticulous search in an area that went beyond the restricted area at the scene of the accident, no scattered aircraft parts could be found, reinforcing the assumption that the intact aircraft structure had crashed against the ground.
MSS Announces a Research Protocol to Find the Obesity Gene
She leads a research project on finding the gene for childhood and adolescent obesity, which is supported by specialists from the IPN.
The Instituto Mexicano del Seguro Social - IMSS (Social Insurance Institute of Mexico) announced that it is conducting a research project on the discovery of the gene for obesity in children and adolescents under the title "Genetics of childhood and adolescent obesity", with the aim of finding the genetic markers associated with obesity.
Miguel Cruz López, head of the Unidad de Investigación Médica en Bioquímica (Department of Medical Research, Biochemistry Focus) at the Clinic Hospital de Especialidades del Centro Médico Nacional Siglo XXI, explained that an interdisciplinary team consisting of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers had been formed.
This team is supported by specialists and postgraduate students from the Instituto Nacional de Salud Pública (INSP) and the Centro de Investigación y de Estudios Avanzados (Cinvestav) of the Instituto Politécnico Nacional (IPN).
The population is invited to participate in the study, which will take place at the IMSS sports fields in the valley of Mexico, where tests with children and adolescents will be carried out every Saturday from 8: 00 am.
He stressed that the investigation began at the Cuauhtémoc sports field (in the western part of the state of Mexico) and has continued since October 8 at the Nezahualcóyolt sports field (in the eastern part of the state of Mexico).
When the target of 500 to 600 investigators is reached, the study will be continued at the Independencia sports field (south of the capital district) and completed at the Morelos sports field (north of the capital district).
He said the aim of the study was to learn about the factors and role of genetics in the development of obesity and to identify risk factors in Mexican children and adolescents for the prevention of chronic degenerative diseases.
On the occasion of World Diabetes Day, he stated that it is intended that three thousand children and adolescents aged between six and 14 years should complete nutrition-related questionnaires with the consent and under the supervision of their parents.
They are also asked questions about their physical activity and family history of disease in order to control risk factors that could lead to diabetes or kidney failure.
He went on to say that on these Saturdays the examiners would be measured (weight, height, waist circumference), their blood pressure would be controlled and blood values such as glucose levels, triglycerides, cholesterol, insulin and genetic factors would be determined (attempts to identify genes related to childhood obesity).
Cruz López stressed that this study was carried out in response to health workers' concerns about the alarming weight gain of young people.
"The health surveys carried out in 1999 and 2006 showed that in just under six years the proportion of obese boys had increased by 77 percent and that of girls with obesity by 47 percent. Obesity had also increased dramatically," stressed the IMSS specialist.
He stated that the search for genetic markers is justified because the genetic history of Mexico's population is different from that of other peoples.
He stated that an average of 65 percent of Mexicans are of American descent, 30 percent are of European descent, and 5 percent are of African descent, which is reflected in genes associated with diabetes and obesity.
More generally, he explained that the genetics of obesity are expressed in the inability to burn the excess energy (calories) that we consume, so that it is stored in the form of fat.
The researcher said that the direct benefit for the study participants would be a comprehensive examination of the children to determine whether they were overweight or obese.
It would even examine the occurrence of dark skin folds in the neck and on the inner arm (acanthosis), which indicate the probability of metabolic disorders and diabetes in the preliminary stage.
All information would be treated confidentially and communicated to the parents in writing by the doctors. Doctors would explain to the parents all measurement results and suggest lifestyle changes that are appropriate for the prevention of illnesses.
Cruz López explained that there are three fundamental factors responsible for overweight, obesity and other chronic diseases: lack of exercise, that is, lack of exercise in everyday life, spending most of the day watching TV and using transport instead of walking short distances.
The high calorie intake, i.e. an increased consumption of sugared beverages and carbohydrates (tamales, bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) together with a high fat and protein intake, as well as the genetics to be analysed in this research project.
Asphalt from the UNAM prevents potholes
Rafael Herrera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry at the Mexican University UNAM develops polymer-modified asphalt to make the mixture more resistant to weather conditions and temperature fluctuations
If the signs from the road surface were to be observed, it would not be necessary to repair almost 200,000 potholes if the rainy season breaks out in the Zona Metropolitana del Valle de México (metropolitan area of the valley of Mexico), said Rafael Herrera Nájera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) at UNAM, and assured that if the laying out and maintenance of the asphalt surface were done appropriately, the number of potholes would be significantly reduced or even completely avoided.
In his lecture "Potholes from a Technical Perspective", held on the occasion of the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory for which he is responsible is developing asphalt modified with polymers in order to produce a mixture similar to asphalt, but with greater mechanical resistance at both high and low temperatures.
According to Herrera Nájera, this type of modified asphalt should be used in areas with extremely hot climates, such as some cities in the north of the country, to improve the behaviour of the road surface and thus avoid potholes.
He explained that asphalt - the heaviest part of petroleum - is a hydrocarbon compound, one part of which has a high molecular weight - the so-called asphalts - and the other part a low - the so-called malthenes. Together, they give the road surface its characteristic viscous elastic behaviour.
The elastic behaviour of the asphalt means that it behaves like a liquid at high temperatures of almost 180 ° C, at 120 ° C it is very viscous and at 50 ° C almost solid, while at very low temperatures it becomes brittle.
"This means that the resistance of the asphalt on the roads is not uniform, but changes in one day depending on weather conditions and temperature fluctuations," the chemical engineer explained.
The FQ researcher noted that most of the streets of Mexico City have a flexible surface composed of six layers of material, the last three of which contain asphalt.
Between the top layers there was a wear layer of asphalt consisting of small stones bathed in asphalt and then solidified.
Every single stone of this wear layer was bathed in asphalt.
If the vehicles move on it and forces are generated, this layer enables a good distribution of forces in the road surface.
"If it were modified asphalt, the forces would be distributed even better," said the chemical engineer.
"Over the wear layer," he said, "a final layer is laid out, the so-called base layer, which consists of tiny stones, i.e. sand that has also been bathed in asphalt.
Since this layer is in contact with the vehicle tyres, it requires a greater mechanical force than the wear layer and it must produce friction.
This road surface receives and distributes most of the forces, so the base layer also needs an adequate thickness and the material of which it is made must be maintained.
The weather conditions, especially humidity and temperature fluctuations, are other important factors to consider, especially the water, "he said," because it significantly affects the behaviour of the wear layer.
When the terrain becomes wet, water penetrates the layer and re-emerges only with difficulty, causing softening of all layers of the road surface and consequently the occurrence of potholes.
When a pothole occurs, "he said," the top layer is removed first, and the wear layer is only damaged afterwards. However, the damage is not immediate, it is a process that should be maintained by appropriate maintenance programs at the first signs. "
The member of the Sistema Nacional de Investigadores (National Research System of Mexico) explained that the vehicle load is another important cause for the occurrence of potholes. Therefore, the thickness of each layer of the road surface must always be proportional to the vehicle load and it must be ensured that this regulation is adhered to in order to avoid frequent potholes.
Rafael Herrera pointed out that there was still a lot of research to be done, for example on asphalt emulsions, which were already on the market in other countries, and with which the potholes could be repaired easily and without applying high temperatures.
