Such was the work of the doctor who identified the corpse of Alfonso Cano
A Lophoscopist from Cali went down in history as the man who identified "Alfonso Cano".
The work of these officials plays a key role.
On November 4, a Lophoscopist of the Public Prosecutor ’ s Office (CTI) arrived from Cali as the man who confirmed the identity of the leader of the FARC (Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia): "Alfonso Cano" by comparing the fingerprints.
Of the seven Lophoscopists in the department of the CTI, this week Eliazar González had on-call duty, a man from Puerto Tejada who has been involved in criminal investigations for 21 years.
At the beginning of his career, González worked in the communities of Chocó, where he often had to spend five days in the jungle to reach the place where the bodies he was supposed to identify were located.
In 2000, he moved to Valle and after completing the necessary courses, he specialised in the examination of the skin exposed to friction, i.e. the palms of the hands and feet.
During the week of action against the so-called Alfonso Cano, Eliazar was told to pack clothes for at least three days.
Something great awaited him.
Friday night he flew in a helicopter from Palmira to Cauca.
He knew that he should identify two corpses and that there was a suspicion that one was the one of the man who had led the oldest guerrilla in the world. Therefore, he should take the ten-finger print of Guillermo León Sáenz (his real name).
However, when he reached the place where the corpse was with the person being examined, he could not identify him because of his physical appearance, which did not resemble the pictures he had seen in the mass media.
He had no beard, was dressed like a local farmer, wore no glasses, and was much thinner.
But fingerprints do not lie.
Armed with a magnifying glass, ink, a planting trowel, and a flashlight, Eliazar compared the fingerprints of the corpse to those on the impression sheet.
He had seen correctly: It was "Alfonso Cano".
That same night, this man from Puerto Tejada was in charge of informing the Secretary of Defense, Juan Carlos Pinzón, that he was indeed the head of the FARC.
Auf Spurensuche
For a dactyloscope of Sijín in Cali, the tribute given by the president Juan Manuel Santos to Eliazar González at a press conference on the fight against "Cano" was very important.
Many people do not know our work.
Dactyloscopy is an exact science without error rate, which can be a key factor in resolving a crime.
Lophoscopists not only identify corpses, they also support investigations into murder and robbery and confirm the identity of the persons arrested.
When they are arrested, many criminals present false identity documents or they have none.
We take their fingerprints and search for them in the database.
The researcher told us that in case of theft he had to tear a piece of wall out of a house, because the thief had supported himself exactly at this point with his hand, when he pulled out a safe filled with jewelry and money.
"Walls are difficult because their surfaces are not suitable for fingerprinting, but in this case we could take the impression of the whole hand and identify the offender who participated in several thefts," he recalled.
The fingerprints can also be used to exonerate or burden murder suspects.
Recently a dead man was found surrounded by brandy bottles.
In the investigation, it was suspected that a family member might be suspect, and indeed a fingerprint on the bottle coincided.
Although this does not guarantee that he is the murderer, he is associated with the place where the crime was committed.
A dactyloscopist from the CTI explained that "the fingerprints are taken from the object with chemical or physical reagents."
When they appear, a trowel or ribbon is used to carry them.
Afterwards the prints are sent to the Asif, that is the criminal database, or to the civil registry office.
"The problem is that there are still many Colombians without identification documents," explained the expert from the CTI.
He said that not everything was the way it was portrayed in the TV ’ s SCI series.
Just as not everything that glitters is gold, not everything you touch is a fingerprint.
But nevertheless it can be used, if one accomplishes an appropriate comparison.
