Energy policy:
Facts should prevail over dogmas
If there is an issue that cannot be dealt with on the basis of short-term considerations or emotions, it is certainly energy policy.
The availability and cost of electricity have a direct impact on the purchasing power and competitiveness of companies.
It is reasonable to take an election meeting as an opportunity to reflect on this issue and on the position of nuclear energy.
The debate will only bear fruit if it explores all the economic, social and environmental consequences of the proposed options.
The French should base their opinion on objective facts, rational data.
Although there are 7 billion people on the planet, demographic evolution is driving a doubling of electricity demand by 2050, so that an enormous proportion of the world ’ s population does not have to forego a vital element.
At the same time, it is necessary to alleviate the scarcity of fossil resources in order to continue producing electricity without forgetting the imperative need to reduce greenhouse gas emissions, an issue that has disappeared from the ecological debate in order to combat climatic irregularities.
The Fukushima accident does not change any of these parameters.
Therefore, Germany remains isolated in its decision to abandon nuclear power.
This is not the case in Belgium, which is subjecting its decision to the necessity of finding a substitutable replacement source, nor in Switzerland, which only plans to build nuclear power stations of the last generation.
The UK, Finland, Poland, the Czech Republic, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India and Brazil, to name but a few, continue to pursue their projects with determination.
For its part, the United States decided after Fukushima to add another unit to its park by reopening the Three Mile Island plant, which had been shut down after the nuclear accident.
Although the German model based on renewable energy sources is sometimes presented as a model, reality contradicts the discourse.
The election in Berlin will be reflected in an increase in the price of electricity, an increase in energy dependence on Russia in particular due to the increased use of imported gas, and an increase in CO2 emissions from gas-fired and coal-fired power plants.
All of these unpleasant effects will be felt within a few months.
The Danish case gives us food for thought.
On the one hand, Denmark is the European championship leader in wind energy, from which it obtains 30% of its electricity, and on the other hand, it is one of the largest users of coal and gas, alternating with wind energy; for this reason, its CO2 emissions and its electricity price are 65% and 50% higher than the corresponding European average.
Thanks to the consistency of our energy policy, our neighbours are paying a 40% higher electricity bill than our French households.
Since the price of energy is a key competitiveness factor in the globalised economy and a source of stability for industry on national soil, French companies have an advantage because of the cheapest electricity in Europe.
Any significant reduction in nuclear power would therefore lead to a sharp increase in the price of energy, which would make noble statements about the reindustrialization of our country and the defense of purchasing power an illusion.
Surveys have shown that this is a price that the vast majority of French people are not prepared to pay, just as they have shown resistance to the principle of this energy source.
Let us remember that the energy policy of our country has made it possible to create an industry with 125 000 direct and 410 000 induced jobs.
Due to its strong export character, it brings a host of specialised small and medium-sized enterprises to international markets and makes them creators of countless jobs.
If France were to decide to abandon nuclear power, a large proportion of these SMEs would fall victim to it, and the EUR 6 billion a year of capital goods and nuclear energy exports would shrink more and more.
What electrician would hire an EPR designed to function for sixty years if the demise of his producer is pre-programmed?
In order to solve the energetic equation one has to admit that there is just as little a miracle cure for the production of electricity as there is a work of the devil.
The low-carbon solutions for the use of nuclear power and renewable energy developed by Areva testify to the complementarity of energy sources.
Maintaining the highest possible level of safety is an absolute imperative for nuclear power.
In France, we have a safety authority which carries out uncompromising and transparent controls in existing factories, such as the one in Flamanville.
Their work teams, who have made a name for themselves because of their professionalism, are just too obsessed with the idea of security.
Within 50 years, the nuclear industry has experienced three serious incidents.
Only one, at Three Mile Island, has occurred under normal operating conditions, with no consequences for man or the environment.
At Chernobyl, the drama was conjured up by reactor construction and blameless human error.
At Fukushima, some seem to forget that the accident was caused by two natural disasters of unprecedented proportions, which caused the deaths of several tens of thousands of people.
The nuclear industry will learn the same lessons from this accident as it did after the two previous ones.
As a result of this approach, as well as a cooperation between the safety authorities of the French and German operators and designers of nuclear power plants, the EPR is a draft that enables it to resist such phenomena.
Since it is considered desirable among the electrical engineers to build a nuclear power plant, a halt in Flamanville would be a fabulous gift to the competition of Areva and EDF, allowing them to take the lead in the inevitable development of nuclear power.
It is indispensable and legitimate to look for the best energy bouquet for our country, but it would be irresponsible to let emotions, dogmas and party manoeuvres dominate a debate that also determines the economic, social and financial situation of our country.
Is immigration a burden or an opportunity for the economy?
The immigration policy of Nicolas Sarkozy has been criticized from many angles - overloading of police, judicial and administrative organs due to a policy subjected to the figures, compatibility of this policy with the status of a "country of human rights", as France had called itself.
Recently, the newsreels were dominated by official harassment of foreign students, and the Minister of the Interior announced casually (see Libération of 23 May) that France "does not need talents, bricklayers or waiters from abroad."
But this policy has rarely been analyzed from an economic point of view.
There is a broad consensus on this subject between the right and the left.
On the right, the tone was taken by Jacques Chirac, who in 1976 declared that '900,000 unemployed, including over 2 million immigrant workers, should not be a problem for a country', on the left by Michel Rocard, who in 1990 had stated that 'France cannot absorb all of the world's poverty'.
The only difference is the degree of generosity
Fear of invasion of the national soil by hordes of Polish plumbers was shared by both the right and the left in 2005.
Both camps perceived immigrants as a burden on the economy and French society.
The only difference is the degree of generosity one is willing to admit to immigrants.
In his programme, François Hollande confines himself to banalities which indicate that cooperative development enables us to solve our "migration problems".
This idea of immigration as a burden, as a problem, may have an impact on elections; however, it is economically costly.
As economists Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron remind us in a recent book that summarizes the latest findings on immigration (Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 p.), there is a broad consensus among specialists on the positive impact of the influx of immigrants on economic growth, wages, and jobs in immigration countries.
Restricting immigration would weaken growth and damage the labour market situation.
Fears of migrants ’ influence are based on the notion that they threaten to substitute local workers, especially the less skilled, by exerting pressure on their wages.
Experience shows, however, that immigrants are, in fact, much more complementary than domestic wage labourers, as they focus on occupations in sectors that are unexploited in terms of employment.
The low-skilled immigrants work in sectors that do not attract domestic wage labourers, the more qualified immigrants work in dynamic sectors where training is not adapted to the labour supply.
Positive wage effect
Just as a surgeon would have difficulty working in a country with a shortage of anaesthetists, this complementarity between locals and migrants also has a positive effect on wages and the domestic labor market.
Giovanni Peri has thus calculated that a 1% increase in the flood of immigrants will bring about a long-term, inclusive increase in real wages of between 0.6% and 0.9%.
And this without taking into account the fact that the diversity of ideas brought in by immigrants is conducive to economic growth (large proportion of naturalized immigrants among American Nobel laureates; Google, Intel, Paypal, eBay, and Yahoo were founded by immigrants).
Migrants also contribute net to social systems, in European countries on average around 1% of the total budget.
The World Labour Organisation estimates, for example, that a person immigrating to Germany at the age of 30 earns a net contribution (income minus expenditure) to the public budget of around 150,000 euros on average over his or her lifetime.
Nicolas Sarkozy wanted to make the missing points "with the teeth" at the beginning of his mandate.
These said teeth, which should deter the immigrants, achieved however exactly the opposite effect.
Europe invented democracy, now it remains to think European democracy through
Democracy is a precious good; it is also a delicate good.
The European continent should be able to remember for itself who, after their invention in Athens more than two thousand years ago, endured the entire 20th century with the tragedies of the First World War, totalitarianism, the Holocaust, the Gulag, but also Franco's in Spain, Salazar's in Portugal and the supreme in Greece.
Some might have thought that exercising the right to vote was enough, and in the most direct way possible, to see democracy prevail over its enemies once and for all.
One knows since Napoleon "the small one" that it was a characteristic of the attitude of mind.
Universal suffrage, which is a necessary condition of democracy, is not a sufficient condition for this and can just as well become an "instrument of oppression", as the Republican philosopher Etienne Vacherot put it at the time.
No, democracy requires much more: a public space, a public spirit, values, organisation, separation and control of powers, education, enlightenment, an economic and social community spirit, a jurisprudence.
The crisis in Europe in which we find ourselves is an economic crisis, but it is also, and above all, a political and democratic crisis.
The change of attitude in the Greek True and False Referendum would have been doubly instructive in this respect: on the one hand, the need for a vigorous return of politics, but on the other hand, the disturbing feeling of its impossibility, its inappropriateness.
This ambivalence should be considered obsolete.
The truth is that the frontlines of the democratic struggle have shifted today, and Republican soldiers, or at least most of them, are no longer heading in the right direction.
