"Contactless" chip cards become common property
The world fair for chip cards opens its doors on Tuesday in Villepinte near Paris in an optimistic attitude.
According to Eurosmart, 2011 was supposed to end with an 11% increase in global sales of microprocessor chips (EC-cards, SIM cards, telephone), with more than 6 billion units sold.
The most important segment here is contactless technology, which enables payments on public transport or for purchases by simply holding the card to a reader.
This year 460 million contactless smart cards should be sold worldwide compared to 320 million a year earlier!
Its market share should increase even further in 2012 (580 million expected units) and represent more than 10% of the global chip card market (6.925 million cards).
Europe is gaining ground on contactless payments, having long lagged behind the Asia-Pacific region.
Some 26 million visas are already equipped with this functionality, and 75,000 payment terminals accept it.
In France, the beginnings are rather modest: only 400,000 contactless visa cards were distributed.
Consumer markets, however, are creating steam.
Carrefour has therefore issued 2.5 million contactless Pass MasterCards this year.
In order to speed up, it is now necessary for banks to equip their customers with these cards.
"Two major French financial institutions have committed themselves to systematically distributing bank cards with contactless chips to their customers in the future," announced Gérard Nébouy, Director General of Visa Europe France.
Banks test payment by mobile phone
However, this is only the first step towards becoming the means of payment of the future: the mobile phone.
A miniscule percentage of devices is currently equipped with the necessary NFC (Near Field Communication) technology to carry out these transactions.
"They have fallen behind".
"But they should at least experience a real upward trend next year."
"We expect to sell 80 to 120 million units worldwide in 2012," says Marc Bertin, Chairman of Eurosmart.
But the banks are taking the initiative.
The Crédit Agricole announced yesterday the start of a test run in Caen, which will run from December to next June.
The iPhones of some 200 customers and employees will be equipped with a capsule that allows contactless payment.
BPCE operates a similar project in Strasbourg and Marseille.
And Société Générale also said yesterday that it was preparing to launch an offer that would allow its customers to make contactless mobile payments.
Terrorist front of course, from the Sahara to Nigeria
Paris is concerned about relations between al-Qaeda in the Islamic Maghreb and the Boko Haram sect.
The long-suspected relationship between the terrorist group al-Qaeda in the Islamic Maghreb (Aqmi) and the Nigerian sect Boko Haram seems to be confirmed.
On Sunday, the Algerian Deputy Foreign Minister Abdelkader Messahel himself confirmed that Algiers had now "gained certainty" about this.
"The way in which both organisations operate and the relations between the secret services indicate clear cooperation," he said without going into any further detail.
Paris seems to make a similar analysis.
The investigation into the kidnapping of two French people in Niger last January has revealed interfaces.
The following day, Antoine de Léocour and Vincent Delory, kidnapped by Aqmi supporters in a restaurant in Niamey, were allegedly killed at the same time as several of their kidnappers during an operation carried out by the French special forces.
French and Nigerian investigators reportedly found several telephone chips belonging to the terrorists in the rubble on the scene.
Terrorist axis
The analysis of the telephone calls leads to several interlocutors based in Mali, Niger and Nigeria.
According to Radio France Internationale (RFI), the investigators are particularly interested in the numbers of two interlocutors: one leads to a Nigerian who has spent a long time in Maiduguri, a town in northern Nigeria that was the cradle of Boko Haram; the other leads to a man who is considered to be close to the Aqmi and the sect.
"This is progress, but there is no doubt that we have to wait for clearer evidence before we can speak of operational cooperation between Aqmi and Boko Harem."
"However, it is conceivable".
"It has been known for years that the sect receives financial and intellectual support from the outside and that it is increasingly active," says Nigerian researcher Kunle Amuwo.
In recent months, the "support" has become increasingly evident, as have Boko Harem's speeches and modes of operation, which now point to the involvement of suicide bombers and the use of increasingly complex explosives that bear the same signature as those used by Aqmi.
Since then, the international community, starting with Washington, has put pressure on Abuja to address the problems caused by Boko Haram.
Indeed, the Nigerian authorities have long regarded the group as a community of Illuminists, to which no particular attention needs to be paid.
Rapid success
Boko Haram, founded in 2002 in Maiduguri near a mosque, a school and the fundamentalist Iman Mohammed Yusuf - which in Haoussa means "Western education is a disgrace" - is pursuing the establishment of an Islamic Emirate in the Muslim north of Nigeria.
In this penniless region, the merger is rapidly gaining ground.
It is politicizing and demanding strict adherence to Sharia law, while its affiliated activists are engaged in the struggle against the godless central government.
The activists are initially targeting churches, bars and authorities.
In 2009, Boko Haram activists were particularly active with their intensified attacks on the commissariats.
The reaction on the part of Abuja, however, is as usual indifferent.
The army surrounds the city, 800 people are killed.
Muhammad Yusuf, who was taken prisoner, is killed in prison.
As a result, the sect is becoming increasingly radical, leaving its strongholds in the north.
Last Christmas, she confessed to an assassination attempt in Jos that claimed 80 lives, followed by another in Abuja.
In June, Boko Haram is blamed for a suicide bombing that took place in the secure police headquarters in Abuja, the first of its kind.
In August, the local headquarters of the United Nations will be the primary international target.
The formation of a terrorist axis in Africa, which is to lead from Mauritania over Nigeria up to Somalia, concerns since then all security experts.
While the Aqmi have occupied Mali and Niger, the Somalis of Al Shabaab operate in Kenya, Boko Harem seems to be a new threat in the center of the continent.
Last week, during a meeting with President Goodluck Jonathan in Nigeria, Alain Juppé warned of Boko Harem and expressed his willingness "to share all the information".
The World According to Republican Presidential Candidates
Mitt Romney, Herman Cain, and Rick Perry compete in simplification and ignorance about China, Iraq, and assistance to Israel.
Can a crisis-weakened America lead a complex world of simple, not to say simplistic, ideas?
Listening to Republican presidential candidates, voters may almost get that impression.
