The population rather appreciates the positive balance of national security under Obama, which has eliminated Bin Laden.
Since Iraq, it has been wary of military interventions that lead to paralysis.
And Obama surprises more appropriately, arguing that America must be rebuilt economically to revive its leadership.
Nord Stream, new gateway to Russian gas in Europe
The Nord Stream gas pipeline, which runs on the bottom of the Baltic Sea and connects Western Europe directly to Russia, has been put into operation.
It will provide gas for the equivalent of 30 million households.
The Russian gas giant Gazprom wanted to celebrate this event with splendour and glory.
Last Tuesday, more than 500 invited guests, including four heads of state and government, attended the inauguration of the new Nord Stream gas pipeline, which connects Russia and Germany directly below sea level, accompanied by orchestral sound and a gourmet buffet.
German Chancellor Angelika Merkel, Russian President Dmitri Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon, and his Dutch counterpart Mark Rutte have symbolically joined forces to control the valve that transports Russian gas to the Western European network.
The new gas pipeline is intended to supply 27.5 billion cubic metres of additional Russian gas per year to Western Europe through a first pipeline of 1,224 km in length, which connects the region of St Petersburg with Mecklenburg in Western Pomerania.
A second pipeline, which will enable a total supply of 55 billion cubic metres of gas - the equivalent of France's total consumption - is to be completed by the end of 2012.
And the possibility of the construction of a third line on the same route is already hinted at.
For Gazprom, the timely and precise completion of this enormous structure looks like a victory.
The project was highly controversial in Poland and the Baltic States.
In fact, the Nord Stream pipeline will enable the direct supply of gas to Germany, avoiding any route through third countries (Poland or Ukraine) by land.
That is why these two countries are losing a little of their power: it is becoming more difficult for them to exert pressure on Russia by threatening to close access to Western European markets.
Warsaw, the city most heavily involved in the debate, was not afraid to compare the Northern Stream Pipeline with a "new German-Soviet pact" in connection with the alliance between Hitler and Stalin for the occupation of Poland in 1939.
This means that the issue is politically extremely sensitive.
Western Europe has gained even greater security of supply by supporting this Russian project.
This, however, at the expense of exhausting European energy, as the project has opened a gap between Western and Eastern Europeans.
In barely five years, Russia has managed to impose its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich Western countries, which have high gas consumption and are running out of gas.
"This gas pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, it is a new artery that connects us in an organic way", confirmed François Fillon at the inauguration of the gas pipeline, pointing out to what extent the major gas contracts are also important from a political and economic point of view.
All of this explains the broad smile of the numerous Gazprom managers in Lubmin regarding the gas supply.
The construction of this gas pipeline is also an outstanding technology.
The underwater pipe consists of steel with concrete coating, which is to protect it from ship anchors.
It rests on the bottom of the sea, at a depth of about 200 meters.
Minefields dating from the Second World War had to be avoided during their construction.
"About hundreds of mines had to be removed or destroyed as a precaution," stated Jens Müller, spokesman for Nord Stream.
In addition, increased measures had to be taken to protect the fauna and flora.
The pipe is a long snake made of metal, weighing as much as 242 Eiffel towers, which is uninterrupted over the entire length: neither by valves nor maintenance stations.
A control platform was planned off the coast of Sweden, but the project managers refrained from doing so because the Swedes were not keen on seeing a Russian state-owned company establish itself permanently on the level of their coasts.
"In the event of an accident, we close the gas passage in less than a minute," Jens Müller specified.
In the event of a leak, the gas in the gas pipeline escapes into the air.
This case, however, is considered by the designers to be less likely, since the welds were estimated to be resistant to one leak per 100,000 years.
State monitoring of the gas pipeline is ensured both by an underwater robot, which is controlled for external observation purposes from a seagoing vessel, and by a device that circulates inside the gas pipeline.
It has the shape of a cigar, measures one meter in diameter, is inserted into the inside of the pipeline and moved by the gas pressure.
After three complete days of moving through the line at a speed of 3 meters per second, the device, upon arrival, provides the most accurate information on possible deformations of the metal.
The gas pipeline was designed to operate for fifty years without the slightest need for repair.
The gas circulation is simply ensured by pressure.
This is 200 bar at the entrance, 100 bar at the exit point.
Five societies have joined forces to realize this project.
However, the management remains in the hands of Gazprom, which holds 51% of the shares.
Furthermore, the German companies E. ON and BASF are affiliated (15.5% each) as well as the Dutch Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies have formed a business community called Nord Stream, which is responsible for the construction and operation of the gas pipeline.
It is based in Zug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then leased to that company the entire capacity of its gas transport, on renewable twenty years of contract.
"Gazprom will pay for the total capacity, no matter how much gas is actually transported," specified Jens Müller.
The financing of the gas transmission construction was secured to 30% by shareholders as well as to 70% by bank loans.
The total labour costs should amount to EUR 7.4 billion for both pipelines.
For GDF Suez, for example, the investment amounted to EUR 240 million.
However, the minority shareholders are certain to recover their expenses, since Gazprom alone bears the liability risk.
The gas pipeline emerges from the Baltic Sea along a sandy, pine-forested coastline near Lubmin.
The 4.5 metre high valves form the gas outlet.
Sensors measure pressure, temperature and other characteristics of the incoming gas before it is transferred to the German gas pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, this terminal has been supplied with one million cubic metres of Russian gas per passing hour.
At full capacity this would be 3 million cubic metres per hour and 6 million in 2012.
Moleskine, a brand notebook.
Founded by an Italian company about fifteen years ago, Moleskine now wants to give writing a new style.
It has a flair of adventure, of hours spent writing by candlelight.
The notebook of Moleskine is easily recognisable, with its black, rectangular cover, its elastic band, the egg-shelled pages, as if aged over time.
The Moleskine Notebook as we know it today, however, was created in 1997.
The Italian company Modo Modo, based in Milan, decided at the time to launch a distinguished design notebook.
Maria Sebregondi, the company ’ s specialist consultant at the time, is in charge of launching the new product onto the market.
The notebook was inspired by a traditional production technique called Mole Skin, which refers to a cotton varnish used for upholstery, for example.
This type of notebook was in great demand among writers and travelers.
"Moleskine has revived an old and almost forgotten object that was considered an icon of avant-garde artists until the 20th century," explains Maria Sebregondi, who is now responsible for brands at Modo Modo.
Success comes.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales increased by 26% and established themselves with sales of 12.7 million pieces.
This is far from the usual production of the first years, in which only 3,000 notebooks were designed.
Moleskine crosses the Italian border and is exported to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
It is difficult to make a snapshot of the buyers, as the notebook inspires business people as well as students and professionals.
Moleskine has the image of a cosmopolitan, cultured and open-minded customer.
The small Italian company, which initially employed 12 people, now employs over 100 people and has had two offices since 2008; one in Milan, the other in New York.
The company distributes its notebooks in bookstores, on Internet portals such as Fnac, in small boutiques in city centres and knows how to assert its identity.
"We have followed the zeitgeist and its new writing needs, which exist despite the upswing of the E" mails ", explained Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural trait is accompanied by the development of the Moleskine company: recently, the brand launched an exhibition called "Detour", in which architects and artists exhibited their own notebooks.
In August, the company also launched a leopard binding at the Locarno Film Festival.
Moleskine benefited from its success and this cultural zeitgeist and was able to diversify its products: bags, calendars, pens, computer cases... The brand features the whole range of articles.
A success that brings envy on the scene: In autumn 2006, Modo was acquired by the investment fund SG Capital Europe, today ’ s Syntegra Capital, thus opening a new chapter in the history of the Moleskine company.
Why does the unemployment rate of disabled workers remain so high?
Approximately 19% of people with disabilities are looking for a job.
The 15th Work for the Disabled Week begins today.
Despite a purposeful public policy introduced in 2005, the unemployment rate for disabled people is always twice as high as the average: 19% against 9% of the population as a whole.
Discouraging?
"No," says Éric Blanchet, Director General of the Adapt Association, which is organising the 'Working for the Disabled Week'.
"The progress made in fifteen years is considerable."
"At the time, the unemployment rate was not double, but triple."
"Nevertheless, a great deal remains to be done."
However, it must be said that many obstacles remain for disabled unemployed people before they get a job.
It is more common with older people: 37% are older than 50 years (17% on average).
They have a low level of qualification: 80% of them do not have a baccalaureate and only 10 000 disabled people are among the 2.3 million students with a higher level of education.
Lastly, long-term unemployment is also very widespread: 53% of the disabled, compared with 38% on average.
In short, there are so many criteria which make it difficult to get back to work and which are "at the heart of the problem", said Christian Grapin, CEO of Tremplin, an association founded in 1992 to help companies recruit disabled workers.
So much for the practical brakes.
Remains the unspoken, the attitudes which, while certain, develop slowly.
A study carried out in April by the IMS Entreprendre association for the magazine La Cité stated that the managers surveyed had "a low level of knowledge regarding the disabled", which was "over-represented" by "people in wheelchairs, mentally or intellectually deprived".
As a result, private companies with more than 20 employees still have a long way to go to reach the 6% employment target for disabled workers, which was laid down in a 1987 law.
These latter figures, dating from 2008, indicate a quotient of 2.6%.
“We are now close to the 3%, ” says Pierre Blanc, Director General of Agefiph, the organization charged with collecting contributions from companies that violate this law.
The proof is that the number of "fee-paying" establishments has decreased, as has the sum of the amounts paid between 2007 and 2011, from 59,000 to 46,000 (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
"The law of 2005, which provides for increased contributions, created a strong pressure on companies," said Pierre Blanc.
"But this improvement also expresses a real insight, especially among the large groups of companies."
According to the Ministry of Labour, only 59% of establishments with between 20 and 49 employees employ disabled workers, while companies with between 100 and 199 employees employ 82%.
